window.COURSE_DATA = [{"id": "important-contacts", "title": "Important Phone Numbers", "start": 3, "end": 3, "category": "Reference", "text": "Life Savers 117\nPHONE NUMBERS\n\nEssex Terminal Railway Office 519-973-8222\n\nOn Duty Yard Coordinator EXT. 2280\n\nCell # 519-257-5558\nTony De Thomasis, President & CEO EXT. 2380\n\nTerry Shields, Vice President EXT. 2480\n\nJack Weston, Director of Operations 519-551-9327\nCell #\nKelly Woodman, Corporate Human Resource Manager EXT. 2400\n\nDirect Line 519-946-3664\nDale Lambier, Corporate Health and Safety EXT. 2420\n\nCell # 226-280-5958\nDrag Cvetkovski, Superintendent EXT. 2270\n\nCell # 519-890-1497\nRyan Jean, Assistant Superintendent EXT. 2390\n\nCell # 226-758-9720\nDarryl Potter, Road Master EXT. 2290\n\nCell # 519-567-0684\nJeff Mayne, Chief Mechanical Officer EXT. 2300\n\nCell # 519-817-7110\nKaleena Belanger, Freight Office Manager EXT. 2340\n\nJames Taylor, Diesel Mechanic EXT. 2330", "takeaways": ["Jack Weston, Director of Operations 519-551-9327", "Kelly Woodman, Corporate Human Resource Manager EXT. 2400", "Dale Lambier, Corporate Health and Safety EXT. 2420", "Jeff Mayne, Chief Mechanical Officer EXT. 2300"]}, {"id": "health-safety", "title": "Health and Safety Policy Statement", "start": 4, "end": 4, "category": "Core Safety", "text": "ETR\nTHE ESSEX TERMINAL RAILWAY COMPANY\nHEALTH AND SAFETY POLICY\n\nThe Essex Terminal Railway is committed to safeguarding the health and well -being of our employees,\ncustomers and the general public by creating and maintaining a safe working environment. Safety is our top\npriority and will not be compromised.\n\nETR and its employees at every level are responsible and accountable for overall safety initiatives.\nEmployees are responsible to perform their duties in accordance with established health and safety policies,\nprocedures, laws and regulations giving consideration for their safety, the safety of co -workers and the\nsafety of our customers. The commitment to a safe workplace will be accomplished through complying with\nall applicable federal governmental regulations and sound industry safe work practices.\n\nManagement is committed to the health and safety of our employees. Our goal is the provision of an\naccident and industrial disease-free work environment. This shall be accomplished by ensuring that hazards\nare guarded against or eliminated, safe procedures are established, and policies and rules are developed\nand maintained.\n\nETR will provide the training, personal protective devices, appropriate and properly maintained equipment\nand avenues of communication to ensure a safe, secure workplace.\n\nThe personal commitment and active participation of all levels of management, employees, and contractors\nis required and expected. By fulfilling our safety responsibilities everyone will share the prosperity that a\nsafe workplace brings.\n\nEmployees will, as a condition of employment, commit to the principle that:\n\nSAFETY IS EVERYONE’S RESPONSIBILITY", "takeaways": ["The Essex Terminal Railway is committed to safeguarding the health and well -being of our employees,", "customers and the general public by creating and maintaining a safe working environment. Safety is our top", "ETR and its employees at every level are responsible and accountable for overall safety initiatives.", "Employees are responsible to perform their duties in accordance with established health and safety policies,"]}, {"id": "violence-statement", "title": "Workplace Violence, Harassment and Discrimination", "start": 5, "end": 5, "category": "Respectful Workplace", "text": "ETR\nWORKPLACE VIOLENCE, HARASSMENT and\nDISCRIMINATION POLICY STATEMENT\n\nEssex Terminal Railway is committed to the prevention of workplace violence, harassment (including\ndiscrimination and sexual) and, as the Employer, is ultimately responsible for worker health and safety. We will\ntake reasonable steps to protect our workers from violence and workplace harassment of all sources.\nViolent behaviour and harassment in the workplace is unacceptable from anyone. This policy applies to all\nmanagers, supervisors, workers, contract personnel, contractors, visitors, members of the public on Essex\nTerminal Railway premises and domestic/intimate partners. Everyone is expected to uphold this policy and to\nwork together to prevent workplace violence and harassment.\nThe Workplace Violence and Harassment Program is the internal program that implements this policy statement It\nincludes measures and procedures to reasonably protect workers from workplace violence and harassment, a means\nof summoning immediate assistance and a process for workers to report incidents.\nEssex Terminal Railway, as the Employer, will ensure this policy statement and its supporting program are\nimplemented and maintained and that all workers and supervisors have the appropriate information and\ninstruction to address and respond to incidents of violence and harassment in the workplace.\nSupervisors and managers will adhere to this policy and the supporting program. Supervisors and managers are\nresponsible for ensuring the measures, procedures and programs are followed by workers and that workers have\nthe information needed to protect themselves in the workplace.\nEvery worker must comply with this policy and the supporting program. All workers are encouraged to act upon and\nraise any concerns about workplace violence and harassment and are required to report any incidents or\nthreats to the Supervisor/Manager, Human Resources, or Joint Health and Safety Representative.\nAll reported Incidents/complaints of workplace violence and harassment will be investigated and addressed in a\nfair and timely manner, respecting the privacy of all concerned as much as possible.\nBoth management and workers must be dedicated to the prevention of workplace violence and harassment,\nwith an understanding of shared responsibility to meet current applicable health and safety legislation,\nstandards and regulations", "takeaways": ["Essex Terminal Railway is committed to the prevention of workplace violence, harassment (including", "discrimination and sexual) and, as the Employer, is ultimately responsible for worker health and safety. We will", "take reasonable steps to protect our workers from violence and workplace harassment of all sources.", "Violent behaviour and harassment in the workplace is unacceptable from anyone. This policy applies to all"]}, {"id": "federal-violence", "title": "Federal Violence and Harassment Program", "start": 6, "end": 22, "category": "Respectful Workplace", "text": "No. ETR- HR - 012\n\nHUMAN RESOURCES POLICY Effective Date June 20/2025\n\nFederal Violence and Harassment Program Procedure Revision 2021.2\n\n1.0 Purpose\nThis program is in support of ETR’s Workplace Violence, Harassment and Discrimination Policy\nStatement and applies to the Essex Terminal Railway. Essex Terminal Railway, in co-operation with\nour unions, is committed to a healthy, harassment-free and violence-free environment for all\nour employees. ETR has developed a company-wide policy intended to:\n\n• prevent and respond to workplace harassment and violence of any type, and\n• effectively address any incident that might occur\n\n1.1 Application\n\nThis policy applies to all employees, contract personnel, contractors and visitors at Essex\nTerminal Railway who are engaged in work, work-related activities or work-related\nrelationships. It applies to employees, contract personnel, contractors and visitors both on\ncompany property and outside of company property. This policy applies to all incidents of\nworkplace harassment and violence, including sexual harassment and sexual violence, family\nviolence and third-party violence.\n\n2.0 Definition of harassment and violence\nThe Canada Labour Code (the Code) defines harassment and violence at subsection 122(1) as\n“any action, conduct or comment, including of a sexual nature that can reasonably be expected\nto cause offence, humiliation or other physical or psychological injury or illness to an employee,\nincluding any prescribed action, conduct or comment.”\n\n2.1 Harassment\nHarassment can include, but is not limited to any of the following acts or attempted acts:\n\n• spreading rumours or gossip about an individual or group\n• cyber bullying (threatening, spreading rumours or talking negatively about an individual\nonline)\n• threats made over the phone, by email, or through other medium to an employee,\nincluding from an (ex)partner or family member\n• making offensive jokes or remarks\n\n• playing unwanted practical jokes\n• socially excluding or isolating someone\n• stalking or inappropriately following a person\n• tampering with someone’s work equipment or personal belongings\n• vandalizing or hiding personal belongings or work equipment\n• impeding a person’s work in any deliberate way\n• persistently criticizing, undermining, belittling, demeaning or ridiculing a person\n• intruding on a person’s privacy\n• public ridicule or discipline\n• unwelcomed physical contact\n• sexual innuendo or insinuation\n• unwanted and inappropriate invitations or requests, including of a sexual nature\n• displaying offensive posters, cartoons, images or other visuals\n• making aggressive, threatening or rude gestures\n• misusing authority, including:\no constantly changing work guidelines\no restricting information\no setting impossible deadlines that lead to failure, and/or\no blocking applications for leave, training or promoting in an arbitrary manner\n• engaging in any of the actions, conduct and comments outlined above against a person\nbecause of that persons:\no race\no national or ethnic origin\no colour\no religion\no age\no sex\no sexual orientation\no gender identity or expression\no marital status\no family status\no genetic characteristics\no disability, or\no any of the other prohibited grounds that the Canadian Human Rights Act list\n\n2.2 Harassment is not\nHarassment is not any of the following:\n\n• consensual workplace banter and interactions (unless it includes hurtful remarks about\nothers, especially if they pertain to any of the prohibited grounds listed above)\n• reasonable management action carried out in a fair way, such as day-to-day actions by a\nsupervisor or manager related to:\no performance\no absenteeism\no assignments\no discipline, and\no even dismissal (unless it is abusive or discriminatory)\n• every workplace disagreement, if a conflict is poorly handled or left unresolved, it can\nlead to harassment\n\n2.3 Violence\n\nViolence can include but is not limited to the following acts or attempted acts:\n\n• verbal threats or intimidation\n• verbal abuse, including swearing or shouting offensively at a person\n• contact of a sexual nature\n• kicking, punching, scratching, biting, squeezing, pinching, battering, hitting or wounding\na person in any way\n• attack with any type of weapon\n• spitting at a person\n\n3.0 Responsibilities\n3.1 Role of Essex Terminal Railway\n\nThe role of Essex Terminal Railway in relation to harassment and violence prevention includes:\n\n• committing to preventing harassment and violence in the workplace\n• jointly reviewing and, when necessary, updating this policy with the workplace\ncommittee at least once every 3 years or following any change to an element of this\npolicy\n• jointly conducting an initial workplace assessment with the workplace committee\n• jointly monitoring and, when necessary, updating the workplace assessment with the\nworkplace committee when there is:\no a change to the risk factors identified, or\no a change in the effectiveness of the preventive measures that have been\ndeveloped and implemented\n\no in situations where the principal party chooses to end the resolution process but\nthe occurrence is not resolved, or\no in situations where the responding party is not an employee or the employer\n• jointly reviewing the workplace assessment with the workplace committee and, when\nnecessary, updating it\n• jointly developing emergency procedures with the workplace committee\n• deploying the workplace emergency procedures whenever an incident, including an\nincident of family violence or domestic violence, poses an immediate danger to the\nhealth and safety of an employee or there is a threat of such an incident\n• jointly reviewing and, when necessary, updating the emergency procedures with the\nworkplace committee\n• making available to all employee’s information related to support services\n• jointly developing or identifying harassment and violence prevention training with the\nworkplace committee\n• delivering harassment and violence training to all employees and the designated\nrecipient\n• jointly reviewing and, when necessary, updating the training with the workplace\ncommittee at least once every 3 years and following any change to an element of the\ntraining\n• ensuring that the designated recipient correctly follows the resolution process that is\noutlined in the Workplace Harassment and Violence Prevention Regulations (the\nRegulations)\n• for investigations into an occurrence of harassment and violence, providing a final\nsummary of the investigator’s report to the principal party, responding party, and\nworkplace committee\n• jointly determining with the workplace committee which recommendations from the\ninvestigator’s report should be implemented\n• implementing the jointly determined recommendations from the investigator’s\nsummary\n• ensuring the resolution process is completed within 1 year after the day on which a\nnotice of an occurrence is received\n• reporting to the Labour Program employee deaths resulting from occurrences of\nharassment and violence, within 24 hours of becoming aware of the death\n• providing the Labour Program by March 1st of every year an annual report summarizing\nthe data on all occurrences of harassment and violence in the previous calendar year\n• complying with all other aspects of the Regulations and the Code as it relates to\nharassment and violence\n\n3.2 Role of designated recipient\n\nUnder this policy, the HR Manager will act as the designated recipient. The role of the\ndesignated recipient in relation to harassment and violence prevention at Essex Terminal\nRailway includes:\n\n• responding to all notices of an occurrence within 7 days of receiving the notice\n• initiating negotiated resolution with the principal party within 45 days after the day on\nwhich the notice of an occurrence is received\n• reviewing every notice of an occurrence with the principal party against the definition of\nharassment and violence outlined in subsection 122(1) of the Code\n• making every reasonable effort to resolve an occurrence for which a notice has been\nprovided\n• allowing the principal and responding parties the option of participating in conciliation if\nthey both agree to participate and on who will facilitate the conciliation\n• providing notice of an investigation to the principal and responding parties if the\nprincipal party requests an investigation\n• in the case of an investigation, selecting a person to act as an investigator from the list\nof investigators developed jointly by Essex Terminal Railway and the workplace\ncommittee\n• ensuring selected investigators have the necessary knowledge, training and experience\nrequired by the Regulations\n• ensuring investigators provide a written statement indicating they are not in a conflict of\ninterest with respect to the occurrence\n• providing investigators all the information that is relevant to their investigation\n• providing monthly status updates to the principal and responding parties on the status\nof the resolution process\n\n3.3 Role of the workplace committee\n\nThe role of the workplace committee in relation to harassment and violence prevention at\nEssex Terminal Railway includes:\n\n• jointly reviewing and, when necessary, updating this policy with Essex Terminal Railway\nat least once every 3 years or following any change to an element of this policy\n• jointly conducting the workplace assessment with Essex Terminal Railway and making\nrecommendations to Essex Terminal Railway regarding changes that should be made\n• jointly monitoring and, when necessary, updating the workplace assessment with Essex\nTerminal Railway when there is:\no a change to the risk factors identified, or\n\no a change to the effectiveness of the preventive measures that have been\ndeveloped and implemented\n• jointly reviewing and, when necessary, updating with Essex Terminal Railway the\nworkplace assessment every 3 years\n• jointly developing the emergency procedures with Essex Terminal Railway\n• jointly reviewing and, when necessary, updating the emergency procedures with Essex\nTerminal Railway\n• jointly identifying with Essex Terminal Railway appropriate harassment and violence\ntraining\n• jointly reviewing and, when necessary, updating the training with Essex Terminal\nRailway at least once every 3 years and following any change to an element of the\ntraining\n• jointly developing a list of investigators with Essex Terminal Railway\n• where appropriate, checking in with Essex Terminal Railway, if necessary, ensuring\ncontinuous compliance with the Regulations and the Code\n• implementing the preventive measures developed by the workplace committee at the\nlocal workplace level\n• jointly reviewing and updating with Essex Terminal Railway the workplace assessment:\no in situations where the principal party chooses to end the resolution process but\nthe occurrence is not resolved, or\no in situations where the responding party is not an employee or the employer (for\nexample, clients, contractors, former partners)\n\n• referring the results of the above reviews and updates to the workplace committee\nwhere appropriate\n• jointly determining with Essex Terminal Railway which of the investigator’s\nrecommendations from the investigator’s report are appropriate to implement\n\n3.4 Role of employees\n\nThe role of all employees in relation to harassment and violence prevention at Essex Terminal\nRailway include:\n\n• refraining from committing harassment and violence\n• where appropriate and safe, informing a person committing harassment and violence\nthat their actions are inappropriate and unwelcomed\n• reporting all occurrences of harassment and violence to their supervisor or designated\nrecipient when they experience or witness it\n• where appropriate, making every reasonable effort to resolve an occurrence of\nharassment and violence through negotiated resolution if they were a party to an\noccurrence\n\n• cooperating with an investigator and the investigation process related to an occurrence\n• refraining from retaliatory behaviour against the principal party, responding party,\nwitnesses and any other individuals who are involved in the resolution process for an\noccurrence\n• respecting the confidentiality of the information shared throughout the resolution\nprocess of an occurrence\n\n4.0 Factors that contribute to workplace harassment and\nviolence\nThere are a number of factors that can contribute to workplace harassment and violence. These\nfactors can be divided into 5 general categories:\n\n• client characteristics\n• physical work environment\n• work activity/culture\n• job factors, and\n• other external factors\n\n4.1 Client characteristics\n\nWorking with clients that exhibit certain characteristics can put employees at greater risk of\nharassment and violence. This can include working with clients, and their relatives, who may\nlash out at the closest person due to:\n\n• being angry and frustrated with the system\n• having a history of violence\n• a mental health condition, emotional disorder, or a head injury\n• racist, sexist, homophobic, transphobic, ableist or otherwise discriminatory attitudes\nand behaviors\n• being under the influence of drugs or alcohol\n\n4.2 Physical work environment\n\nCertain work environments may lead to harassment and violence. These can include:\n\n• working alone, in small numbers or in isolated or low-traffic areas (for example, isolated\nreception area, washrooms, storage areas, utility rooms)\n• having a mobile workplace\n• working in a poorly designed client area, such as a cramped room or a room that has\npoor visibility of clients\n\n• working in an overcrowded environment\n• working in an environment with high noise levels\n\n4.3 Work activity/culture\n\n• working with the public\n• working with volatile persons (for example, criminal justice system employees who work\nwith inmates)\n• working in an environment that tolerates or promotes racist, sexist, homophobic,\nableist, or otherwise discriminatory attitudes and behaviours\n• working during periods of intense organizational change (for example, strikes,\nprivatization, restructuring, downsizing)\n• working in the same workplace with an (ex) partner who is abusive\n\n4.4 Job factors\n\nAspects specific to a job, such as mental and physical demands of the job, can result in\nadditional hazards that may lead to harassment and violence. This can include:\n\n• lack of control over how work is done\n• excessive workload\n• unreasonable or tight deadlines leading to high stress\n• confusing, conflicting or unclear job or roles\n• ambiguous or complicated reporting structures\n• lack of job security\n\n4.5 Other external factors\n\nOther external factors that can result in harassment and violence include:\n\n• Family violence or domestic violence, such as a family member or (ex) partner:\no threatening an employee or co-workers either verbally or over the phone or\nemail\no stalking the employee\no verbally abusing the employee or co-workers\no destroying the employee or organization’s property\no physically harming the employee or co-workers\no using work time or workplace resources to monitor or attempt to control the\nactions of an (ex) partner\n\n5.0 Harassment and violence prevention training\nEssex Terminal Railway will provide all of its employees with a harassment and violence training\ncourse. This course will cover:\n\n• elements of the work place harassment and violence prevention policy\n• the relationship between workplace harassment and violence and the prohibited\ngrounds of discrimination under the Canadian Human Rights Act\n• how to recognize, minimize and prevent work place harassment and violence\n\nAll new employees will receive training within 3 months after the day on which their\nemployment begins. Further, all employees will receive this training again at least once every 3\nyears.\nThe following groups will receive training on their obligations in relation to harassment and\nviolence at least once every 3 years:\n\n• supervisors\n• managers\n• directors, and\n• Designated recipient\n\n6.0 Outline of the resolution process\nBelow is a summary of the resolution process. It includes how a principal party, or witness, can\nsubmit a notice of an occurrence.\n\n6.1 Representation\nAt any time during the resolution process, an employee may be accompanied or represented by\na:\n\n• union representative, or\n• a person of their choosing\n\n6.2 Notice of an occurrence\n\nYou are encouraged to notify (the designated recipient) if:\n\n• you are an employee who is experiencing or have experienced harassment and violence\nin the workplace, or\n• you are an individual (employees or non-employees) who witnessed an occurrence of\nharassment and violence in the workplace\n\nNotify the designated recipient by telephone at (519-973-8222 x 2400), or by email at\nkwoodman@etr.ca\nThe designated recipient will ask the employee or individual to fill out a form, in which they\nprovide the following information:\n\n• the name of the principal party and the responding party (if known)\n• the date of the occurrence\n• a detailed description of the occurrence\n\nIf an employee or individual is not able to provide this information in written form, they may\nprovide this information to the Designated Recipient verbally. The Designated Recipient will\nthen transcribe the information for them on the form.\nPlease note that, in order to proceed with the resolution process, it is mandatory to provide the\nname or identity of the principal party who was involved in the occurrence. If you do not\nprovide the name or identity of the principal party, the occurrence will not be further reviewed.\nEssex Terminal Railway cannot reveal the identities of the parties involved in the resolution\nprocess for an occurrence to either the workplace committee or union without the consent of\nthe parties. However, the identities of the parties may be revealed to each other as part of the\nresolution process.\n\n6.3 Negotiated resolution\nNegotiated resolution is a form of informal resolution where the principal party meets with the\nemployer or designated recipient to:\n\n• discuss the occurrence\n• clarify what was submitted in the notice of occurrence, and\n• attempt to reach resolution\n\nDuring negotiated resolution, the designated recipient will ask the principal party to meet,\neither in person or by phone, with the designated recipient. This meeting is for an initial\ndiscussion regarding the occurrence. During this discussion, the designated recipient and the\nprincipal party will review the notice of occurrence that they received against the definition of\nharassment and violence in the Code. Together, they will try to determine whether the\noccurrence meets the definition. If both the designated recipient and the principal party agree\nthat the occurrence does not meet the definition, then they will deem the occurrence as\nresolved. If the designated recipient and the principal party do not agree as to whether the\noccurrence meets the definition, and the principal party wishes to continue with the resolution\nprocess, then the principal party has the option of either:\n\n• continuing with negotiated resolution, or\n• pursuing conciliation and/or an investigation\n\nIf the principal party wishes to continue with negotiated resolution, they must inform\nthe designated recipient of this decision. The designated recipient will schedule a series of\nmeetings with the principal party. At the meetings, where applicable, the responding party will\ndiscuss the occurrence and attempt to achieve resolution. All parties involved must make every\nreasonable effort to resolve an occurrence for which notice has been provided and those\nefforts must begin no later than 45 days after the day on which that notice is provided. The\nresponding party does not have to be informed of the principal party’s notice of occurrence or\nbe involved at this stage of the resolution process. This is only if the principal party does not\nwish for them to be notified or involved. The designated recipient can arrange for any of the\nfollowing meetings:\n\n• meetings with only the principal party\n• meetings with the principal party, responding party and the designated recipient\n• meetings between the principal party and the designated recipient with concurrent but\nseparate meetings between the responding party and the designated recipient\n\n6.4 Conciliation\n\nA principal party and responding party may engage in conciliation at any time during the\nresolution process. However, conciliation can only proceed if both the principal party and the\nresponding party agree to engage in conciliation. They must also agree on the person who will\nfacilitate the conciliation. However, conciliation can only proceed if an investigator has not\nprovided their final investigation report.\nThe principal party and responding party are required to inform the designated recipient of\ntheir desire to participate in conciliation. The designated recipient will then facilitate discussion\naround the selection of a conciliator who is agreeable to both parties. The designated recipient\nwill also schedule time for both parties to meet with the conciliator.\n\n6.5 Investigation\nThe principal party may request an investigation at any time during the resolution process. If\nthe principal party wishes to proceed with an investigation, they must inform the designated\nrecipient. The designated recipient will then:\n\n• provide notice of an investigation to the principal and responding party, and\n• select an investigator from the list of investigators noted in Addendum 1 of this policy\nwho are clearly identified as having received appropriate training as per Section 28 (1)\nRegulation (SOR/2020-130)\n\nThe investigator chosen by the designated recipient shall be agreed upon by the principal and\nthe responding party to ensure no conflict of interest, but if there is no agreement within 60\ndays after the day on which notice was provided, a person from among those of whom the\nCanadian Centre for Occupational Health & Safety identifies shall be determined as the\ninvestigator.\n\nThe selected investigator will investigate the occurrence and provide Essex Terminal Railway a\nreport outlining:\n\n• a general description of the occurrence\n• their conclusion, and\n• their recommendation to eliminate or minimize the risk of a similar occurrence\n\nEssex Terminal Railway will then provide a copy of this report to the principal party, responding\nparty and the workplace committee.\nThe report will not reveal, directly or indirectly, the identity of the persons who were involved\nin the occurrence or the resolution process for the occurrence.\nEssex Terminal Railway and the workplace committee will then meet to determine which of the\nrecommendations in the investigator’s report are to be implemented. Essex Terminal Railway\nwill implement those recommendations within 1 year of receiving the notice of occurrence.\nEssex Terminal Railway may take into consideration the findings in an investigator’s report\nwhen applying disciplinary measures. However, disciplinary measures will also depend on the\nfindings from a separate administrative investigation that the Essex Terminal Railway will\nconduct in some circumstances.\nEssex Terminal Railway cannot use the findings in an investigator’s report for any of the\nfollowing purposes:\n\n• replenishment of sick leave\n• granting of any additional paid or unpaid leave\n• monetary remuneration for damages\n\nHowever, the section Recourse avenues in this policy describes other recourse methods an\nemployee can pursue.\n\n7.0 Protection against reprisal\nParties involved in an occurrence are prohibited from seeking retaliation. If you experience any\nretaliatory action or threat of retaliatory action from the responding party, witnesses,\nmanagement, or other people within or outside the organization, please inform the Designated\nrecipient immediately.\n\n8.0 Workplace assessment\nThe designated recipient and the workplace committee will conduct a joint review. If necessary,\nthey will update the workplace assessment if an employee submits a notice of an occurrence\nand the resolution process cannot proceed for any of the following reasons:\n\n• the principal party chooses to end the resolution process at any point during the\nresolution process but the occurrence is not resolved\n\n• the responding party is not an employee or the employer (for example, the responding\nparty is a member of the public, a client, or an (ex)partner or family member)\n\nThe purpose of the review and update of the workplace assessment is to:\n\n• determine what happened, taking into account the circumstances of the occurrence\n• determine whether all risk factors have been appropriately identified\n• develop new preventive measures, if needed, to mitigate the risk of a similar occurrence\n\n9.0 Emergency procedures\nIf a harassment and violence occurrence poses an immediate danger to the health and safety of\nan employee, or if there is a threat of such an occurrence, notify the Emergency Coordinator,\nand Senior Management, call 911 for emergency services (police, fire and ambulance).\nBelow is a summary of the emergency procedures that the Essex Terminal Railway must\nimplement in various types of situations.\n\n9.1 Violence in the workplace\nIf you witness or experience violence at work:\n\n• remove yourself from the situation if you can\n• inform your manager or seek help from a co-worker immediately\n• if your manager is the perpetrator, notify the DR (HR Manager)\n• if your physical security or well-being is threatened, if possible, call 911\n\nIf you are dealing with a violent person:\n\n• stay calm\n• try to calm the other person or diffuse the situation (if you can)\n• avoid saying or doing anything that could aggravate the situation\n• avoid eye contact or sudden movements that can be perceived as threatening\n• respect the person’s personal space\n• continue the conversation with the person only if the person calms down\n• tell the person that you understand the reason for their anger\n• if the behavior persists, end the conversation\n• politely notify the person that you will leave the work area or ask them to do so\n• notify your manager or seek help from a co-worker immediately\n• if the person refuses to leave the premises and the situation escalates call 911\n\n9.2 Active shooter\n\nIf you witness an incident involving an active shooter outside the building:\n\n• stay out of sight (away from windows) and warn colleagues, clients and visitors\n• leave the area at risk\n• when safe to do so, call 911, and other building occupants\n• if you cannot evacuate the building safely, lock outside doors.\n• wait for instructions from first responders\n\nIf you witness an incident involving an active shooter inside the building:\n\n• stay calm\n• if you can do so safely, leave the area immediately\n• warn others, as many as possible, without attracting the attention of the assailant\n• if you can do so safely, call 911 and notify other building occupants\n• lock the doors or barricade yourself in a room using furniture\n• block the windows, close the office blinds\n• if the workspace has no door, hide under your desk or where you cannot be seen\n• if you are in a washroom, remain there, if safe to do so\n• silence your cellphone, turn off radios and computers\n• if you cannot escape, remain silent and hide until first responders arrive\n• wait for instructions from first responders\n\n9.3 Bomb threat\n\nIf you are made aware of a bomb threat by telephone:\n\n• listen to the caller calmly and do not interrupt them\n• try to get as much information as possible, such as:\no when the bomb is supposed to explode\no where the bomb is located\no description of the device\no reason for the call or motivation for the threat\no telephone number on the display screen (if possible)\n• remember any details you can about the caller, such as:\no approximate age\no gender\no accent\no level of nervousness\no any background noise\n\n• call 911 and inform your manager\n• remain available to provide information to first responders\n\nIf you are made aware of a bomb threat by e-mail:\n\n• save the email (or letter)\n• send it immediately to the Emergency Coordinator and Senior Management\n• The Emergency Coordinator in consultation with senior management, shall notify the\npolice and fire departments, and following their advice and direction shall:\n• Initiate a search for the devices; or\n• Initiate partial or entire facility evacuation.\n• If a search uncovers a suspicious package, Do Not touch, notify Emergency Coordinator\nand senior management\n\n10.0 Privacy protection\nEssex Terminal Railway is committed to the protection of the privacy of the persons involved in\nan occurrence. As such, the workplace committee are not permitted any involvement in the\nresolution process of an occurrence. Only the Designated recipient will engage in the resolution\nprocess with the principal party and responding party. Further, we will not permit an\ninvestigator to disclose in any report it produces and distributes the identity of any of the\npersons involved in an occurrence or the resolution process for an occurrence. This includes the\nprincipal party, responding party, witnesses and any other individuals interviewed by the\ninvestigator.\n\n11.0 Recourse avenues\nEmployees can pursue multiple recourse avenues for their occurrence. This includes:\n\n• filing a grievance with the Union\n• pursuing recourse under the Canadian Human Rights Act with the Canadian Human\nRights Commission, or\n• pursuing recourse under the Criminal Code\n\n12.0 Support measures\nSupports and resources related to family violence are available at Ending Violence Canada -\nSupport Services.\n\n13.0 Notices submitted in bad faith\nNotices of harassment and violence that are identified throughout the resolution process as\nhaving been made in bad faith may be subject to disciplinary action\n\n14.0 Complaints related to employer non-compliance with\nthe Code or Regulations\nIn accordance with section 127.1 of the Code or Regulations, if you, as an employee believe\nthat there has been a contravention of the Code as it relates to an occurrence of harassment\nand violence, you may make either a verbal or a written complaint to your supervisor or to Kelly\nWoodman, Human Resources Manager. Notify Kelly by telephone at (519-973-8222 x2400), or\nby email at kwoodman@etr.ca\n\n15.0 Definitions\nThe following definitions apply to this policy:\n\n• Designated recipient- The Corporate Health & Safety Specialist in consultation with the\nCorporate Human Resources Manager are chosen by Essex Terminal Railway, to whom a\nnotice of an occurrence may be submitted.\n• Occurrence means an occurrence of harassment and violence in the workplace\n• Principal party means an employee or employer who is the object of an occurrence\n• Responding party means the person who is alleged to have been responsible for the\noccurrence in a notice of an occurrence provided to the designated recipient\n• Witness means a person who witnessed an occurrence of harassment and violence or is\ninformed of an occurrence by the principal party or responding party\n• Workplace means any place where an employee is engaged in work for the employee’s\nemployer as per 122(1) of the Code\n• Negotiated resolution - Any form of communication between the participating parties\nto discuss the occurrence and attempt to reach agreement on possible actions to\nresolve the occurrence.\n• Conciliation - A discussion or series of discussions that is mediated by The Corporate\nHealth & Safety Specialist, who is a neutral third party will facilitate the discussion(s)\nand assist the parties involved in reaching resolution. All parties involved in conciliation\nmust mutually agree to participate in conciliation\n• Resolution process - All the avenues of resolution – negotiated resolution, conciliation\nand investigation.\n• Emergency Coordinator - DAY SHIFT – SUPERINTENDENT (Assistant Superintendent- If\nSuperintendent not available)\no AFTERNOON SHIFT – TRAINMASTER / YARD COORDINATOR (where\napplicable if Trainmaster unavailable)\n▪ MIDNIGHT SHIFT (IF APPLICABLE) – SUPERINTENDENT /\nASSISTANT\no SUPERINTENDENT / TRAINMASTER\n\nADDENDUM 1\n\nThe following is the list of internal Investigators for selection:\n\nKelly Woodman, Corporate Human Resources Manager\n\nDale Lambier, Corporate Health & Safety Specialist\n\nJack Weston, Director of Operations\n\nRyan Jean, Assistant Superintendent\n\nETR shall select a third-party investigator when required from The Registry of Investigators.", "takeaways": ["prevent and respond to workplace harassment and violence of any type, and", "effectively address any incident that might occur", "spreading rumours or gossip about an individual or group", "cyber bullying (threatening, spreading rumours or talking negatively about an individual", "threats made over the phone, by email, or through other medium to an employee,"]}, {"id": "irs", "title": "Internal Responsibility System (IRS)", "start": 23, "end": 29, "category": "Core Safety", "text": "No. ETR-H&S-033\n\nHEALTH & SAFETY POLICY Effective Date July 7/2025\nInternal Responsibility System -Federal Revision 2025.1\n\n1.0 POLICY STATEMENT\n\nThe Internal Responsibility System (IRS) is part of the Canada Labour Code Part II. As this\npolicy pertains to the health & safety of all employees. Very simply put, the IRS is all\nabout teamwork.\nEveryone in the workplace has a shared responsibility to make sure that the workplace\nis healthy and safe for everyone, from senior management to the worker. The IRS will\nset out the specific duties each role has in ensuring a safe and healthy workplace.\n\n2.0 SCOPE\n\nThis policy applies to all employees of The Essex Terminal Railway Company. This includes,\nSenior Management, Managers and Supervisors and all full and part-time employees.\n\n3.0 ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\n\nEMPLOYER DUTIES\n\nConsult the Workplace committee on the development, implementation and monitoring\nof a program for the prevention of work place hazards. This program must also provide\nfor the education of employees in health and safety matters.\nConsultation must also occur between the employer and the Workplace committee in\nthe development, implementation and monitoring of a program for the provision of\npersonal protective equipment, clothing and devices.\nThe employer is to consult the Workplace committee to plan the implementation of\nchanges in the work place that may have an effect on the health and safety of\nemployees. Similar consultation is to take place at the Workplace committee level in the\ndevelopment of other health and safety policies and programs.\n\nWork place committees will be consulted in the development, implementation and\nmonitoring of a program for the prevention of unique work place hazards that also\nprovides for the education of employees in health and safety matters.\nWork place committees will be consulted in the implementation of the work place\nchanges and the implementation and monitoring of any programs developed through\nconsultation with the workplace committee. Employers are required to cooperate with\nwork place committees.\n\nSpecific duties of employer\n125 (1) Without restricting the generality of section 124, every employer shall, in\nrespect of every work place controlled by the employer and, in respect of every work\nactivity carried out by an employee in a work place that is not controlled by the\nemployer, to the extent that the employer controls the activity,\n• ensure that all permanent and temporary buildings and structures meet the\nprescribed standards;\n• install guards, guard-rails, barricades and fences in accordance with prescribed\nstandards;\n• except as provided for in the regulations, investigate, record and report, in\naccordance with the regulations, all accidents, occurrences of harassment and\nviolence, occupational illnesses and other hazardous occurrences known to the\nemployer;\n• provide prescribed first-aid facilities and health services;\n• provide prescribed sanitary and personal facilities;\n• provide, in accordance with prescribed standards, potable water;\n• ensure that the vehicles and mobile equipment used by the employees in the\ncourse of their employment meet prescribed standards;\n• provide every person granted access to the work place by the employer with\nprescribed safety materials, equipment, devices and clothing;\n• ensure that the levels of ventilation, lighting, temperature, humidity, sound and\nvibration are in accordance with prescribed standards;\n• comply with prescribed standards relating to fire safety and emergency\nmeasures;\n• ensure, in the prescribed manner, that employees have safe entry to, exit from\nand occupancy of the work place;\n• provide, in the prescribed manner, each employee with the information,\ninstruction, training and supervision necessary to ensure their health and safety\nat work;\n\n• maintain all installed guards, guard-rails, barricades and fences in accordance\nwith prescribed standards;\n• ensure that each employee is made aware of every known or foreseeable health\nor safety hazard in the area where the employee works;\n• ensure that the machinery, equipment and tools used by the employees in the\ncourse of their employment meet prescribed health, safety and ergonomic\nstandards and are safe under all conditions of their intended use;\n• ensure that the work place, work spaces and procedures meet prescribed ergonomic\nstandards;\n• adopt and implement prescribed safety codes and safety standards;\n• ensure that every person granted access to the work place by the employer is\nfamiliar with and uses in the prescribed circumstances and manner all prescribed\nsafety materials, equipment, devices and clothing;\n• ensure that the activities of every person granted access to the work place do not\nendanger the health and safety of employees;\n• ensure that employees who have supervisory or managerial responsibilities are\nadequately trained in health and safety and are informed of the responsibilities they\nhave under this Part where they act on behalf of their employer;\n• ensure that members of work place committees receive the prescribed training in\nhealth and safety and are informed of their responsibilities under this Part;\n• develop, implement and monitor, in consultation with the work place committee, a\nprescribed program for the prevention of hazards in the work place appropriate to\nits size and the nature of the hazards in it that also provides for the education of\nemployees in health and safety matters;\n• where the program referred to in paragraph (z.03) does not cover certain hazards\nunique to a work place, develop, implement and monitor, in consultation with the\nwork place committee, a prescribed program for the prevention of those hazards\nthat also provides for the education of employees in health and safety matters\nrelated to those hazards;\n• consult the work place committee to plan the implementation of changes that might\naffect occupational health and safety, including work processes and procedures;\n• consult the work place committee in the implementation of changes that might\naffect occupational health and safety, including work processes and procedures;\n• ensure the availability in the work place of premises, equipment and personnel\nnecessary for the operation of the policy and work place committees;\n• cooperate with the work place committees in the execution of their duties under\nthis Part;\n\n• develop health and safety policies and programs in consultation with the work place\ncommittee;\n• respond in writing to recommendations made by the work place committees within\nthirty days after receiving them, indicating what, if any, action will be taken and\nwhen it will be taken;\n• provide to the work place committee, a copy of any report on hazards in the work\nplace, including an assessment of those hazards;\n• ensure that the work place committee inspects each month all or part of the work\nplace, so that every part of the work place is inspected at least once each year;\n• when necessary, develop, implement and monitor a program for the provision of\npersonal protective equipment, clothing, devices or materials, in consultation,\nexcept in emergencies, with the work place committee;\n• take all reasonable care to ensure that all of the persons granted access to the work\nplace, other than the employer’s employees, are informed of every known or\nforeseeable health or safety hazard to which they are likely to be exposed in the\nwork place;\n• meet with the health and safety representative as necessary to address health and\nsafety matters;\ntake the prescribed measures to prevent and protect against harassment and\nviolence in the work place, respond to occurrences of harassment and violence in\nthe work place and offer support to employees affected by harassment and violence\nin the work place;\n• ensure that employees, including those who have supervisory or managerial\nresponsibilities, receive training in the prevention of harassment and violence in the\nwork place and are informed of their rights and obligations under this Part in\nrelation to harassment and violence;\n• undergo training in the prevention of harassment and violence in the work place;\n• ensure that the person designated by the employer to receive complaints relating to\noccurrences of harassment and violence has knowledge, training and experience in\nissues relating to harassment and violence and has knowledge of relevant\nlegislation;\n• post and keep posted, in a conspicuous place or places where they are likely to come\nto the attention of employees, the names, work place telephone numbers and work\nlocations of all of the members of work place committees;\n• provide, within thirty days after receiving a request, or as soon as possible after that,\nthe information requested from the employer by a work place committee under\nsubsection 135(8) or (9); and\n\n• consult with the work place committee on the implementation and monitoring of\nprograms.\n\nEMPLOYEE DUTIES\n\nEmployees have a responsibility to take all reasonable and necessary precautions to\nensure their health and safety and that of anyone else who may be affected by their\nwork or activities. Specifically, the Code requires employees to:\n\n• use all safety materials, equipment, devices and clothing that are provided by the\nemployer and are intended to protect the employees;\n• follow procedures that relate to the health and safety of employees;\n• follow all instructions provided by the employer concerning the health and safety of\nemployees;\n• cooperate with any person carrying out a duty or function required by the Code;\n• cooperate with work place committees;\n• report to the employer anything or circumstance that is likely to be hazardous to the\nemployees or any other person in the work place;\n• report to the employer, all work related accidents, occupational diseases or other\nhazardous occurrences that have caused injury to the employee or any other person;\n• report to the employer, any situation the employee believes to be a contravention\nof Part II of the Code, by the employer, another employee or any other person;\n• comply with every oral direction or written direction given by a health and safety officer\nor an appeals officer;\n• respond in writing to a health and safety officer's direction or report when requested to\ndo so by the health and safety officer.\n\nNobody knows a work place better than the people who work in it. Part II of the Canada Labour\nCode gives the work place parties a strong role in the identification and resolution of health and\nsafety concerns.\nBASIC RIGHTS TO EVERY WORKER\n\nThe right to know\n\nThrough the provisions of the Code, employees have the right to be informed of known or\nforeseeable hazards in the work place and to be provided with the information, instruction,\ntraining and supervision necessary to protect their health and safety.\n\nThis right to know is strengthened by ensuring that the methods of communication are\nappropriate for all employees, including employees with special needs.\nThrough their health and safety committees or representatives, employees are given the right\nto have access to government or employer reports relating to the health and safety of\nemployees, but do not have access to medical records of any person except with that person's\nconsent.\n\nThe right to participate\nAs health and safety representatives or committee members, employees have the right and the\nresponsibility to participate in identifying and correcting job-related health and safety concerns.\nEmployers who employ 300 or more employees are required to establish a policy health and\nsafety committee. The purpose of the policy committee is to handle issues that are\norganization-wide in nature. Because these types of issues go beyond a single work place, there\nis a need for a more strategic or global approach for their resolution.\nPart II of the Canada Labour Code further provides for employee participation through the use\nof an internal complaint resolution process.\nThe right to refuse dangerous work\nAn employee, at work, has the right to refuse dangerous work if he or she has reasonable cause\nto believe that:\n\n• a condition exists at work that presents a danger to himself or herself;\n• the use or operation of a machine or thing presents a danger to the employee or a co-\nworker; and\n• the performance of an activity constitutes a danger to the employee or to another\nemployee.\n\nIn order for an employee to be protected by the Code when exercising the right to refuse, the\nemployee must follow the proper procedure.\n\nWORKPLACE COMMITTEE\n\nA Workplace Committee, as defined under the Canada Labour Code (CLC), is a group\nestablished in federally regulated workplaces to address health and safety\nmatters. These committees play a crucial role in promoting a safe and healthy work\nenvironment by addressing complaints, participating in hazard prevention programs,\nand conducting inspections\n\nEXTERNAL PARTIES\n\nParties and organizations external to the workplace also contribute to workplace health\nand safety. These include the Labour Program's Health and Safety Officers, the\n\nWorkplace Safety and Insurance Board (WSIB), and the health and safety system\npartners. These external parties work alongside internal workplace parties (employers\nand employees) to ensure a safe and healthy working environment\n\n4.0 Responsibility\nAs the employer of The Essex Terminal Railway, we hold the responsibility of ensuring\neverything reasonable is done in the prevention of injury. We as a company will ensure\nour managers and supervisors are handling health and safety issues in our workplaces\nas expected, and are committed to building a strong safety system that will ensure any\nand all health and safety related concerns are addressed and resolved internally.\n\nIt is the expectations of the Company that employees address their concerns with their\nsupervisors first, along with the assistance of the Workplace committee; and follow the\nhierarchy of authority to resolve all health and safety related matters, prior to\ncontacting and using external parties in attempt to resolve health and safety deviations.\n\n5.0 Review\nThis Policy will be reviewed on an annual basis.", "takeaways": ["ensure that all permanent and temporary buildings and structures meet the", "install guards, guard-rails, barricades and fences in accordance with prescribed", "except as provided for in the regulations, investigate, record and report, in", "provide prescribed first-aid facilities and health services;", "provide prescribed sanitary and personal facilities;"]}, {"id": "work-refusal", "title": "Work Refusal and Internal Complaint Resolution", "start": 30, "end": 32, "category": "Core Safety", "text": "THE ESSEX TERMINAL RAILWAY COMPANY\nWORK REFUSAL POLICY\nAn employee who believes on reasonable grounds that there is likely to be an accident or injury to\nhealth arising out of, linked with, or occurring in the course of employment shall, make a complaint\nto the employee’s supervisor.\n\nThe employee and supervisor shall try to resolve the complaint between themselves as soon as\npossible.\n\nIf a resolution cannot be reached between the employee and supervisor, a Health and Safety\nrepresentative and a Company official will jointly investigate the complaint.\n\nIf the work refusal continues after a joint investigation, a Health and Safety Officer will be called to\ninvestigate the complaint.\n\nOn the completion of the investigation, the Health and Safety Officer may,\n\n(a) Issue directions to the employer or employee under section 45 (1) of the Canada Labour Code.\n\n(b) Recommend that the employee and employer resolve the matter between themselves or,\n\n(c) If the officer concludes that a danger exists as described in subsection 128 (1), issue directions\nunder subsection 145 (2) of the Canada Labour Code.\n\nAn employee may not, refuse to use, or operate a machine or thing, to work in a place, or to perform\nan activity if,\n\n(a) The refusal puts the life or safety of another person directly in danger or,\n\n(b) The danger is a normal condition of employment.\n\nAn employee, who refuses to use or operate a machine or thing, work in a place, or to perform an\nactivity, shall remain on the premises and report all pertinent circumstances of the matter to the\nemployer without delay.\n\nIf the employer agrees that a danger exists, the employer shall take immediate action to protect\nemployees from danger. The employer shall inform the Health and Safety Committee of the matter\nand the action taken to resolve it.\n\nTHE ESSEX TERMINAL RAILWAY COMPANY\nINTERNAL COMPLAINT RESOLUTION PROCESS\n\n• Employee refuses to work and notifies employer 128.(6).\n• Employer investigates in presence of employee.\n• Employer writes Employer Report 128.(7.1).\n\nEmployee not satisfies and notifies employer and\ncommittee or\n\nRepresentative 128.(9).\nCommittee or representative investigates in presence of\nEmployee employee 128.(10), and provides a report of investigation\nsatisfied and\nreturns to work. Results and recommendations to employer 128.(10.1).\n\nRevised report if deemed appropriate and\npresented\nEmployer decides Employer provides additional information to committee or\n128.(13). representative 128.(10.2).\n\nDANGER REFUSAL NOT PERMITTED 128.(13)(b). NO\n• Other persons put in DANGER DANGER\n128.(13)(a).\n128.(2)(a)\nEmployer takes • DANGER is a normal condition of\ncorrective action employment 128.(2)(b).\nEmployer provides written\nand notifies\ndecision to employee 128.(15).\ncommittee or\nrepresentative\n128.(14).\nEmployee\nsatisfied and\nreturns to work. Employee continues to refuse and notifies employer 128.(15).\n\nEmployee notifies Minister and presents his reports.\n\nEmployee notifies committee or representative 128.(16).", "takeaways": ["Employee refuses to work and notifies employer 128.(6).", "Employer investigates in presence of employee.", "Employer writes Employer Report 128.(7.1).", "Other persons put in DANGER DANGER"]}, {"id": "fatigue", "title": "Fatigue Management Plan", "start": 33, "end": 41, "category": "Operations", "text": "No. H&S - 12\n\nEffective Date November 25, 2021\nFATIGUE MANAGEMENT PLAN POLICY Revision 2022.2\n\n1. INTRODUCTION\n\nThis Fatigue Management Plan (the ‘Plan’) has been developed pursuant to the requirements of Part\nD of the “Duty and Rest Period Rules” (the ‘Rules’) by the ETR Fatigue Management Working Group\n(‘FMWG’). The FMWG includes designated representatives for the Teamsters Canada Rail\nConference – Train and Engine (the ‘TCRC’). As a shared responsibility between ETR and TCRC, the\nFMWG will monitor the Plan, make recommendations and changes to the Plan in the future. This\nincludes additional modifications to the Plan and supporting processes that will need to be done to\naddress phased in requirements of the Rules as they come into effect.\n\nThe Plan is designed with the intent that the principles of fatigue science will be applied to the\nscheduling process for operating employees and to mitigate risk associated with fatigue. It also\noutlines the goals of the Plan, roles and responsibilities and its application.\n\n1.1. PURPOSE AND SCOPE\n\nThe purpose of this Plan is to provide a framework for a Fatigue Management Program (the\n‘Program’) to manage risks related to fatigue at ETR. The Plan provides the approach that will be\nused to identify, assess, and manage risk related to fatigue for ETR employees who are involved in\nperforming “operating” responsibilities (an ‘operating employee’). As defined in the Rules and used\nin this document.\n\n• Employee means “locomotive engineer, conductor, trainman, yardman, pilot, operator of\nremote-control locomotives and operator of light rail passenger equipment or any person\nwhose preponderance of time is spent in such classifications, who is physically involved in the\noperation of switching of trains, engines and equipment as well as any other persons who\nperform such duties.”; and\n• Operating means “being in control of or engaged in the operation of railway equipment or\nswitching of trades, transfers, engines, or equipment and does not include time spent on\nrailway equipment where the employee is not required to attend the equipment in\naccordance with the Canadian Railway Operating Rules.”:\nThe Program includes all policies and procedures and processes related to fatigue risk management.\nIn addition to the foregoing, any person who performs the duties of an operating employee is\ndeemed to be an operating employee while they are performing those duties. This includes Yard\nCoordinators and ETR Management.\n\n1.2. OPERATIONS/TERRITORY DESCRIPTION\n\nThe Essex Terminal Railway (ETR) is a switching (or short line) railway that runs from the east side of\nWindsor, ON through the Town of LaSalle, ON and Amherstburg, ON. The mainline of the ETR runs in\n\na generally southwest direction for 19 miles in a route that roughly parallels the Detroit River that\nseparates Windsor, ON from Detroit, Michigan.\n\nThe ETR provides switching services for local customers engaged in the industrial, lumber, steel,\nagricultural, scrap metal, alcohol, and liquid petroleum gas (LPG) industry sectors. While ETR does\nnot run any trains, a total of up to 3 roustabout crews may be working simultaneously per day. ETR\ninterchanges with 3 class 1 railroads (CN, CP, CSXT) in Windsor, ON. ETR’s track is not shared with\nany other railways. Deadheading and associated activities such as management of activities relative\nto deadheading are not relevant for the Essex Terminal Railway as all staff members begin and end\nall shifts at the same location due to the total length of track being 19 miles. Away from home\naccommodations are not necessary for employees of the ETR.\n\nCharacteristics of the territory\n\nBecause ETR is a short line railway that operates locally, the territory is contained within Windsor,\nON, LaSalle, ON, and Amherstburg, ON. The ETR provides switching services for pick-up and delivery\nof railcars between facilities and interchange locations at which point a connection to another rail\ncarrier is provided. Given the geographical areas of Canada, some areas may be exposed to\nunpredictable weather, and may submit workers to days which can have extended or short\nexposure to daylight. Working in differing weather and light conditions may have an impact on\nfatigue levels.\n\nTraffic Density\n\n1.3. OBJECTIVES\n\nETR will see objectives for fatigue management related policies, procedures, and processes as they\nare developed. In general, the objectives of all the Program’s policies, procedures and processes are\nto:\n\n• Prevent, mitigate and manage risks associated with fatigue;\n• Maintain or improve operational task performance and safety;\n• Promote and increase awareness of the impact of fatigue and alertness strategies;\n• Enable assessment for levels of fatigue that may affect safe railway operations and/or deem\nan employee as not fit for duty;\n\n• Allow for the effective implementation of fatigue countermeasures; and,\n• Identify roles and responsibilities\nSpecific objectives will be set by a Fatigue Management Working Group in consultation with the\nTCRC Union. Guidelines on fatigue risk management will be referenced in the process of setting the\nobjectives for alignment with industry best practices and standards.\n\nThe Program will be reviewed at least annually by ETR’s Fatigue Management Working Group to\nmonitor how effectively it is achieving its objectives. The objectives may be revised by the Fatigue\nManagement Working Group in consultation with the TCRC.\n\n1.4. DIFFERENCES IN REQUIREMENTS\n\nOperating employees have many opportunities to rest under the Duty and Rest Period Rules and\nTCRC/ETR Collective Bargaining Agreements (CBAs), as amended from time to time. This includes\nemployees operating in assigned and unassigned service. As Operating employees have access to\ncopies of the Rules and CBAs, the opportunities for rest offered by those documents, which\ncontribute, to Fatigue Management have been deemed outside the scope of this document. In the\nevent of a potential conflict, regulations; rules, CBAs and company policies and procedures will\nsupersede the content of this document.\n\n2. FATIGUE MANAGEMENT POLICY STATEMENT\n\nETR will enable employees to perform their duties as safely and effectively as possible by mitigating\nrisks associated with fatigue. To this end, ETR is committed to developing and maintaining a Fatigue\nManagement Program. The objective of the Fatigue Management Program is to prevent, mitigate\nand manage the risks related to fatigue during ETR operations, and to promote health and wellbeing\nfor employees, and for the provision of quality services.\n\n1. DEFINITIONS\nWhere applicable, terms in the document have the same meaning as defined in the Rules.\n\n2. FATIGUE MANAGEMENT ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\nManaging fatigue involves shared responsibility between ETR and its employees. Duties and\nresponsibilities of personnel who have a role in managing fatigue are described in this section.\n\n4.1. ACCOUNTABLE EXECUTIVE\n\n• Is the executive designated under section 8(1) of the Safety Management System 2015\nRegulations.\n• Accountable for ensuring the Program is developed and implemented in accordance with\nthe Plan.\n\n4.2. FATIGUE MANAGEMENT WORKING GROUP (FMWG)\n\n• Membership will include representatives from, at a minimum, management, and the\nrelevant bargaining agent. Representatives to be included:\no Health and Safety Supervisor\no Joint Health & Safety Committee Union Representative\n\no ETR Assistant Superintendent\n• Responsible for providing input on the development, monitoring, and modification/update\nof the Plan and Program. Accountable for ensuring the Plan is developed;\n• Responsible for:\no The development and modification of the Plan\no The development/monitoring/and modification of the Program\no The review/audit of the Program\no The verification of compliance with the Rules\n• The ETR Assistant Superintendent will chair/lead the Fatigue Management Working Group\n(FMWG). The ETR Assistant Superintendent is also responsible for conducting risk\nassessments relating to fatigue.\n\n4.3. ETR MANAGEMENT\n\n• Responsible for working with the FMWG, as needed, to:\no Provide interpretation on relevant regulatory requirements\no Engage with the designated representatives of the TCRC to share and collect input\no Submit notification to the Minister of Transportation of any material revisions to\nETR’s Plan, no later than 30 days following the visit\no Engage with Transport Canada\n• Health and Safety Supervisor is responsible for assisting in the development of fatigue\ntraining. Managers/Supervisors of Operations are responsible for developing and delivering\nfatigue training.\n\n4.4. MANAGERS/SUPERVISORS OF OPERATIONS\n\n• Responsible to read, understand, and comply with the Plan and Program to manage fatigue\nas described in the procedures, policies, and processes:\no Safety Management Systems (e.g., Procedure – Methods for applying fatigue\nscience principles to scheduling).\no Scheduling;\no Training;\no Risk Assessment/Evaluations;\no Recording Duty Period Time;\no Emergency Situations;\no Call-out Processes; and\no Accident and Incident Investigations\n• Accountable for managing the scheduling of Operating Employees\n• Responsible:\no For recording duty period time data\no To record, monitor, and ensure compliance with the Rules:\n- Maximum Duty Period, Emergency Situations\n- Minimum Rest Period\n- Maximum Cumulative Duty Period Time\n- Maximum Time Free from Work\n\n- Provide input on the development, monitoring, and modification/update of\nthe FMP and Program.\no Responsible to ensure employees are fit for duty prior to shift, during shift and as\ncircumstances change throughout their tour of duty.\n- Review employee fatigue management pre-shift self-assessment\n- Review employee fatigue management during shift evaluation\n- Ensure employees are using mitigating strategies if they have a change in\ncategory during any self-assessment\n- Replace or relieve any employee who reports not fit for duty\n• The ETR Assistant Superintendent and or Trainmaster are responsible for delivering fatigue\ntraining.\n\n4.5. OPERATING EMPLOYEES\n\n• Employees are responsible for:\no Being fit for duty;\no Making effective use of rest periods and breaks in order to obtain adequate rest;\no Reporting to Supervisor, before or during a duty period where they are fatigued or\nnot fit for duty;\no Reporting to Supervisor, any situation that may present a fatigue-related risk that\nmay affect safe railway operations.\no Fill out the Fatigue Management Pre-Shift Self-Assessment, hand it into your\nimmediate supervisor for review and report immediately if you’re not fit for duty;\no Fill out the Fatigue Management During Shift Evaluation if an employee believes\nthey are fatigued in a manner that may affect safe railway operation or if an\nemployee believes they are not fit for duty any time after beginning a duty period.\nHand it in to your immediate supervisor for review and record;\no Fill out the Fatigue Management During Shift Evaluation if an employee’s duty\nperiod is scheduled to last more than 10 hours and end between 0001 and 0600.\nHand it into your immediate supervisor for review and record;\no Reporting all duty period time;\no Not accepting an assigned duty period that does not comply with the requirements\nof these Rules;\no Immediately notify the Managers/Supervisors of Operations if they become aware\nthat the assigned duty period would result in the maximum duty period or\nmaximum cumulative duty period time being exceeded;\no Completing all training provided by the railway company and applying the\nprinciples;\no Complying with the Plan, the Program, and all related policies, processes and\nprocedures and the Rule.\n\n5. METRICS AND TARGETS\n\nMetrics and targets for each of the objectives will be identified by the Fatigue Management Working\nGroup. Guidelines on fatigue risk management will be referenced in the process of setting the\nmetrics and targets for alignment with industry best practices and standards. The program will be\n\nreviewed annually by ETR’s Fatigue Management Working Group (FMWG) to monitor how\neffectively it is achieving its targets and objectives. Performance against the targets and objectives\nwill be evaluated by the FMWG in consultation with the ETR Superintendent and H&S\nrepresentatives meeting on an annual basis to discuss any events, near misses, and fatigue reports\nin order to determine if the objectives, targets to meet the objectives, and ways to measure\nachievement need to be modified for the coming year. The targets and objectives may be revised by\nthe Fatigue Management Working Group.\n\nThe targets and objectives will be shared through refresher training.\n\n6. REVIEWING AND UPDATING THE PLAN\n\nThe long-term success of the Plan depends upon ongoing monitoring and evaluation. Appropriate\nmeasurements and metrics will be identified to facilitate the evaluation of the Plan against the\ntargets and objectives. The FMWG will meet annually, or as regulations change, to review the\ndevelopment, implementation and ongoing effectiveness of the Plan and Program or as needed to\naddress significant issues.\n\nThe Fatigue Management Plan will be reviewed annually to determine how effectively it is\nfunctioning and achieving its objectives. The annual review will be conducted by ETR’s Fatigue\nManagement Working Group. Strengths, opportunities for improvement, and issues of significance,\nwill be identified in the annual evaluation. ETR employees will assess their fatigue using a tool based\non the 9-point Karolinska Sleepiness Scale which is based on fatigue science and industry guidance\nto track and trend continuous improvement. Any number of fatigue reports and reports of fatigue\nrelated unfit for duty occurrences will trigger an update to the plan. In addition, any operational or\ndesign changes will trigger an update to the plan. Corrective action to update and/or revise the Plan\nor Program will be developed and tracked by the FMWG. Issues of significance resulting from the\nevaluation of the effectiveness of the FMP will be recorded in writing by the FMWG and addressed\nwith the collaboration of ETR’s joint health and safety committee. Updates to the FMP due to cause\nwill be investigated promptly by the FMWG, and revisions will be tracked on the document itself and\nreviewed with staff members through monthly footboard meetings, and upon orientation of new\nhires. The FMP is updated due to cause as a result of any near miss relating to fatigue, or any\nscheduled changes that may affect the plan.\n\nThe Plan, Program and resource materials will be made available to employees via the ETR Health &\nSafety Board, the ETR Employee Handbook, and training.\n\n7. TRACKING AND RECORDING DUTY PERIOD HOURS\n\nDuty hours will be tracked against the limits in the Duty and Rest Period rules by ETR Assistant\nSuperintendent or Trainmaster and tracked using a shared Microsoft Excel spreadsheet as well as\ncompany electronic payroll software. The tracking and recording duty period hours procedure will\nbe adjusted to include details regarding:\n\n• Duty Period hours needed to account for the following activities:\no Operating\no Administration duties\no Waiting for re-crews or transportation\no Training, and\n\no Meetings\n• Total time spent in accordance with any period or activity.\n\n8. MANAGING EMERGENCY SITUATIONS\n\nETR recognizes the importance of managing fatigue and maintaining fitness for duty during\nemergencies, service interruptions and other unusual operating conditions.\n\nAs defined in the Rules, an “emergency situation means a sudden or unforeseen situation where\ninjury or harm has been sustained, or could reasonably be sustained to employee(s), passenger(s),\nthe public or the environment such as those involving a casualty or unavoidable accident, an Act of\nGod, severe storms, major earthquakes, washouts, derailments or where there has been a delay\nresulting from a cause not known to the railway company at the time employees leave the terminal\nand which could not have been foreseen.”\n\nETR will manage fatigue in emergencies that require an employee to exceed the maximum duty\nperiod of 12 hours by providing adequate coverage from employees on the spare board during the\nemergency. Employees from the spare board will be scheduled in accordance with the collective\nagreement. Subsequent rest periods will be adjusted after extended duty hours due to an\nemergency by providing adequate relief from spare board employees and management as necessary\nand in accordance with section 7.8 of the Duty and Rest Period Rules for Railway Operating\nEmployees. Any employee who has been affected by extended duty hours will have subsequent\nminimum rest periods extended by the amount of time in which the employee’s shift was extended\nby the emergency. In the case of an emergency, the following mitigation measures will be used if a\nduty period needs to be extended:\n\n• Ensure that only safety essential services are performed until a relief crew arrives on-site\n• Ensure a supervisor is always on-site monitoring the safety of workers\nAll reports relating to emergency events will be recorded and retained for a minimum of 2 years.\n\n9. FATIGUE REPORTING\n\nETR employees are required to report their fitness for duty, which can include personal fatigue,\npotential fatigue in others, fatigue hazards, and fatigue-related events. Employees will perform\nfitness for duty self-assessments prior to any duty period and during any duty period if required, by\nusing the Karolinska Sleepiness Scale (KSS) once employees have been trained through footboard\nmeetings on what the KSS is, how to use the KSS to properly perform a self-assessment as well as\nhow and who to report their findings to.\n\n9.1 REPORTING POLICY\nETR employees who report timely, safety-related information such as operational/human errors,\nhazards, observed unsafe acts or conditions or contraventions with legislation, regulations,\nstandards, or laws will not be subject to disciplinary action, retaliation, or adverse consequences by\nETR. This extends to employees reporting unfit for duty, fatigue related issues or risk factors for\nthemselves or other employees.\n\n9.2 REPORTING SYSTEMS\nETR employees are required to report when they feel unfit for duty such as excessively tired and\nrequest relief from duties if necessary.\n\nPrior to a duty period, employees must fill out a Fatigue Management Pre-Shift Self-Assessment\nform and report concerns related to fitness for duty to the Manager/Supervisor of Operations. In\nthe event of an employee or employees reporting unfit for duty after performing a self-assessment\nusing the KSS, a relief employee or relief crew from the spare board will be called in their place.\nEmployees shall be entitled to a two (2) hour call, and their guarantee shall not be reduced, if less\nthan a two (2) hour call is afforded. Conductors/Brakepersons called will make every attempt to\nreport for duty as soon as practicable to cover unknown vacancies in order to reduce crew\ndowntime. Because ETR operates locally within the Windsor-Essex County region and only has 19\nmiles of track, remote locations are not a barrier for a replacement employee providing relief to the\nemployee or employees who report unfit for duty. All ETR employees, including relief employees,\nstart and end their shifts at the same location.\n\nWhile on duty, if an employee believes they are fatigued in a manner that may affect safe railway\noperation or if an employee believes they are not fit for duty any time after beginning a duty period,\nETR employees must fill out a Fatigue Management During Shift Evaluation form. Employees must\nreport any concerns or incidents related to fitness for duty to their Manager/Supervisor of\nOperations. If the employee has changed categories since their pre-shift assessment, they must\nensure to select at least one mitigating strategy that they will implement for the remainder of their\nduty period.\n\nRecording of all instances of unfit for duty will be recorded in company time and attendance\nmanagement system as well as the shared spreadsheet.\n\n10. CALLOUTS AND UNDISTURBED REST\n\nCall Outs and Undisturbed Rest procedures adhered to by the Manager/Supervisor of Operations\nwith ETR will ensure a minimum of 8 hours which employees are assigned to rest and will be\nundisturbed by ETR. In the event of an employee or employees being called out, the\nManager/Supervisor of Operations will first ensure that the employee has rested for a minimum of 8\nhours prior to contacting them. Changes to call out times or methods are not applicable to the ETR,\nas there are no circumstances where the 8 hours of rest will be disturbed.\n\n11. SCHEDULING EMPLOYEES\n\nETR ensures adequate opportunity is provided for rest including a minimum of 8 hours of\nundisturbed rest. The procedure for scheduling employees will be well defined, with specific details\non:\n\n• Bulletins to provide advance notice of a schedule for assigned employees are provided every\n6 months;\n• Access to real-time information regarding employees’ hours of duty periods and rest periods\nprovided to all employees in a shared document which is managed and maintained by the\nManager/Supervisor of Operations with ETR;\n\n• For any changes to operational needs, employees will receive 3 days advance notice and 12\nhours in unforeseen changes to start times in jobs;\n• Managing significant changes to the schedule, including how employees will be notified will\nbe determined by spare board and call-in procedures by the Manager/Supervisor of\nOperations.\n\n12. INVESTIGATIONS\n\nAll accident and incident occurrences determined to be of high risk or where there is an expectation\nthat further study will be able to improve safety performance, will be investigated by collaborating\nwith ETR management, the joint health and safety committee, and the employee or employees\ninvolved in the accident or incident in order to determine if fatigue has been a potential contributing\nfactor. Investigations will include the collection of:\n\n• When the duty period started\n• Hours into the duty period when the event occurred\n• How many hours the employee had been awake\n• Hours of duty and rest for employees in the previous 24 hours and the past 7 days\nThe results of the investigations will be analyzed by comparing them against industry standards, as\nwell as applicable company policies and procedures. Based on the findings of the investigation, ETR\nwill develop and implement corrective measures appropriate to the accident or incident by\nreviewing the details of the case and determining appropriate next steps as well as any relevant\ntraining required as determined by ETR Manager/Supervisor of Operations. ETR will measure the\neffectiveness of the corrective actions by analyzing the results of any recurring incidents or\naccidents recorded on the incident/accident investigation form. Results of the incidents and\naccidents will be communicated to employees and management through bulletins, footboard\nmeetings, and safety bulletins.\n\n13. FATIGUE MANAGEMENT TRAINING\n\nETR will provide both initial group training and refresher training for managing and mitigating\nfatigue to all employees, additional training through footboard meetings and scheduled training\nthroughout employees shifts. The refresher training will be delivered annually and will also be\nincluded in the employee handbook for all new hires starting with ETR. This training includes an\nevaluation of the extent to which participants developed the required competencies, and will\ninclude the following topics:\n\n• Causes and risks of fatigue\n• Symptoms\n• Fatigue management and alertness strategies\n• Fitness for Duty self-assessments using the Karolinska Sleepiness Scale, and the employee’s\nprior work/sleep information\n• Mitigation of fatigue\nETR will make the FMP available to all employees by posting a copy of the most recently revised\nversion on the health and safety board in the yard office, as well as including a copy in the ETR\nemployee handbook.", "takeaways": ["1. INTRODUCTION", "Employee means “locomotive engineer, conductor, trainman, yardman, pilot, operator of", "Operating means “being in control of or engaged in the operation of railway equipment or", "Prevent, mitigate and manage risks associated with fatigue;", "Maintain or improve operational task performance and safety;"]}, {"id": "communications", "title": "Communication Device Policy", "start": 42, "end": 44, "category": "Conduct", "text": "No. HR-009\n\nHUMAN RESOURCES POLICY Effective Date March 30, 2023\nCommunication Device Policy Revision 2023.2\n\nCommunication Device Policy\nIntent\n\nThis policy is to advise of the company’s expectations in regard to any and all communication\ndevices on company, or customer properties whether the device is company issued or is a\npersonal device of an employee. A communication device includes, but is not limited to, cellular\nphones, smartphones, iPods, iPads, gaming devices, or any other form of electronic device.\nInappropriate use of communication devices at work can contribute to serious injuries and\ncause distraction that may interfere with the ability to work safely and may infringe on company\nand customer confidentiality. Headphones and wireless earpieces may interfere with the proper\nuse of personal protective equipment and cause a distraction to employees hearing directions\ngiven by their supervisors and may also restrict their attention to possible hazards in the\nworkplace and will not be permitted.\n\nGuidelines\n\nAll employees must be professional and conscientious at all times when using company issued\nphones. Company cell phones should be limited to use for work-related business and should not\nbe used for everyday personal reasons.\n\nAll other personal use of communication devices is prohibited in the workplace except for while\non breaks and lunches.\n\nResponsibility\n• Employees are not permitted to use Company or personal communication devices\nwhile driving at any time.\n\n• It is against the law to use communication devices while driving. The Company will\nnot pay for infractions incurred while disobeying Company policy or the law.\n• In an emergency, employees are expected to safely pull over to the side of the road,\nin a safe location, free and clear from impeding traffic, before responding to or\nmaking phone calls, sending text messages, emails and voicemail messages.\nEmployees may not resume driving until all communication devices are put away.\n• Employees must be aware that:\no Taking any kind of photographs in the workplace is strictly prohibited without\nthe permission or advisement of the company.\no Recording video or audio conversations on any communication device is\nalso prohibited unless advised by company officials.\no Any use of communication devices during working hours that has not been\nauthorized by the company is prohibited.\no Any social media posts that depict company property or makes mention of\nthe company in any negative manner is strictly prohibited.\n• During working hours, employees should have their devices turned off, and be\nstored in lunch bags or lockers, and may not have it out or on them unless there is\nan emergency or due to radio failure. In cases of emergency, employees should get\npermission from their supervisors to keep their device on them while working, as\nlong as it does not distract the employee from completing their job duties, and it is\nonly used to address the emergency.\n• Employees are expected to focus on work and may not use any communication\ndevice in the workplace for the following:\n1. Engaging in personal conversations\n2. Playing games\n3. Surfing the internet\n4. Checking email, and\n5. Sending or receiving text messages\n• Employees may use communication devices while on breaks and lunches only.\n• Employees who violate this policy will be subject to disciplinary actions, up to and\nincluding termination of employment.\n\nDriving\n\nEssex Terminal Railway has a zero-tolerance policy regarding using a cell phone without a\nhands-free device while driving. For the safety of our employees and others, it is imperative that\nyou pull over and stop at a safe location to dial, receive, or converse on a cell phone if a hands-\nfree device is not available.\n\nEmployees are never to use a hand-held device while:\n\n• Fueling any vehicle or equipment\n• Operating trains, machinery or any other type of vehicle or equipment\nAgain, the company will not be liable for any infractions an employee may receive as a result of\nprosecution due to engaging in this illegal behaviour.\n\nTermination of Employment\n\nIf the employment relationship is terminated, regardless of reason, any company-issued\ncommunication devices must be returned to the company by the employee’s last day of work. If\nthe cell phone is not returned by the employee’s last day of work, the company may recoup the\ncost of the phone through deduction on the employee’s final payroll or may seek the assistance\nof law enforcement in order to recover any stolen property, if applicable.\n\nThe Company reserves the right to amend or alter the terms of this policy should it become\nnecessary, at any time.", "takeaways": ["Employees are not permitted to use Company or personal communication devices", "It is against the law to use communication devices while driving. The Company will", "In an emergency, employees are expected to safely pull over to the side of the road,", "Employees must be aware that:", "Taking any kind of photographs in the workplace is strictly prohibited without"]}, {"id": "trespassing", "title": "Public Trespassing", "start": 45, "end": 45, "category": "Security", "text": "PUBLIC TRESPASSING POLICY\nPURPOSE\n\nSafety at the Essex Terminal Railway is important to all of us. Keeping our workplace safe and\nsecure requires the active efforts of us all. Preventing unauthorized access to ETR facilities, rights-\nof-way and other property can reduce the opportunity for criminals to commit their crimes.\nTrespassing on railway property is dangerous to the trespasser as well as the employee and is\nstrictly prohibited.\n\nRESPONSIBILITY\n\nEmployees who witness trespassers or suspicious activities should:\n• Advise a Supervisor or another employee that a trespasser was observed, your location, and\ncontinue to observe the trespasser from a safe distance to determine if it is safe to\napproach.\n• Never approach a trespasser alone, have another employee accompany you, and carry a cell\nphone or radio to call for help, if required.\n• If you have determined that it is safe to approach, do so politely and ask the trespasser to\nleave the property for their safety. Never attempt to physically remove a trespasser or\nmake physical contact.\n• If the trespasser is a young child (less than 12 years of age) do not leave the site without\nensuring the child’s safety. If the child is un-cooperative, call non-emergency number (519-\n258-6111) and request police assistance to remove the child.\n• Always use caution, courtesy, and common sense when dealing with trespassers. You must\nconsider your own personal safety.\n\nIf there is an immediate threat to the employee’s safety due to acts or threats of violence, report\nthe incident immediately to the local Police through the use of the 911 system.\n\nSupervisors should NOT:\n• Approach a group of trespassers or a suspicious vehicle, instead, notify Police at non-\nemergency phone number (519-258-6111) and continue to monitor (if possible) gathering\nas much information as possible such as, license plate number, color and type of vehicle,\ndescription of trespasser(s) etc.\n• Approach a person that appears aggressive, abusive, or acting in an unusual manner.\n• Approach a trespasser in an isolated location, or any situation that puts you or others in\ndanger.\n• Argue, challenge or threaten trespassers.\n• Attempt to physically remove or make physical contact with a trespasser.", "takeaways": ["Advise a Supervisor or another employee that a trespasser was observed, your location, and", "Never approach a trespasser alone, have another employee accompany you, and carry a cell", "If you have determined that it is safe to approach, do so politely and ask the trespasser to", "If the trespasser is a young child (less than 12 years of age) do not leave the site without", "Always use caution, courtesy, and common sense when dealing with trespassers. You must"]}, {"id": "sharps", "title": "Sharps Disposal Safety Procedure", "start": 46, "end": 47, "category": "Hazard Control", "text": "No.\nH&S-010\n\nHEALTH & SAFETY POLICY Effective Date August 26, 2022\n\nSharps Disposal Safety Procedure Revision 2022.1\n\nSharps Disposal Safety Procedure\n\nScope\n\nEssex Terminal Railway recognizes the safety and protection of employees as one of our\nguiding principles and a key component of sound business performance. It is important that we\nall work to the same safety standards, and that we help each other achieve and maintain these\nstandards by planning safety considerations into all of our work activities. It has been brought to\nthe company’s attention that there has been occasions that Terminals are locating disposed of\nneedles (sharps) in and around Company properties. This policy directs our teams on how to\nsafely address these instances.\n\nPurpose\nTo protect employees and others from blood borne infectious diseases by reducing the risk of\nsharps injuries, such as needle sticks, cuts, and scratches, through safe work practices and the\nuse of safety-engineered protective equipment when disposing of sharps found around the\nproperties of ETR.\n\nPolicy\nEmployees who find needles, syringes, or other medical related sharps on the work premises\nshould not attempt to handle these items at all and must report it to their supervisor immediately\nupon locating.\nThe supervisor will then be required to safely dispose of the sharp waste, treating all needles\nand other sharps devices as biohazardous waste and contaminated.\nSupervisors must ensure they use extreme caution when disposing of such devices, using the\nprovided personal protective equipment (PPE), and following the below steps in order to safely\ndispose of needles found in the workplace:\n\n1. Put on gloves (latex, vinyl, and/or cut resistant) to protect yourself from fluid\ncontamination.\n2. Using tongs or a grabber, pick up needle by the middle of the plastic tube (syringe) with\nthe sharp end facing down. Do not try to recap the needle or break the tip off.\n3. If there are multiple needles, pick them up one at a time.\n4. Place the needle-sharp end first into a puncture proof, sharps container. Keep the\ncontainer closed tightly.\n5. Return the sharps container to the proper storage location.\n6. Remove gloves and wash hands with warm soap and water or use hand sanitizer.\n7. Terminal Managers will be responsible for the disposal of sharps containers when they\nreach the fill line indicated. Sharps disposal bins are located throughout the City of\nWindsor or at your local pharmacy. Do not overfill containers for any reason.\n\nEmployees and supervisors must not:\n\n1. Throw loose sharps in the garbage.\n2. Put sharps in the recycling bin.\n3. Flush sharps down the toilet.\n4. Throw sharps in bushes, parks, or streets.\n5. Never reach into sharps containers.\n\nResponsibilities\nEmployees will be responsible for immediately reporting any sharps found in and around ETR\nproperties to their supervisors, for the protection of all employees. Employees are not to attempt\nto handle or dispose of sharps at any time.\n\nSupervisors are responsible for the safe and proper disposal of sharps that are found or\nreported on company property, using proper PPE provided.\n\nTerminal Managers are responsible for the proper disposal of all sharp containers once they\nreach the indicated fill line.\n\nAll employees are responsible to report any noted problems or concerns associated with the\nsharps container immediately.\n\nAll sharps injuries must be reported immediately to your supervisor and will be recorded on an\nincident report with immediate medical attention being provided by an appropriate medical\nprofessional.\n\nPlease see below for sharps disposal information from the Windsor\nEssex County Health Unit and list below for sharps disposal locations\nin Windsor:\n\nYou can drop off your used sharps at any 24-hour sharps disposal bins located\noutdoors at:\n\n• Street Health Windsor Essex Community Health Centre, 711 Pelissier St.\n• Parking Lot Windsor-Essex County Health Unit, 962 Pelissier St.\n• Parking Lot Windsor-Essex County Health Unit, 972 Goyeau St.\n• AIDS Committee of Windsor 511 Pelissier St.\n• Bruce Park - east side of park facing Church Street\n• Wigle Park - west side of park near McDougall\n• Glengarry/Marentette Neighbourhood - interior courtyard\n• Senator Croll Park - close to Ontario Tourist Information Centre - west side facing\nGoyeau\n• Downtown Transit Terminal - facing Chatham Street\n• Ford City Parkette - corner of Whelpton and Drouillard\n• Dufferin Place - Behind Windsor Fire Headquarters", "takeaways": ["1. Put on gloves (latex, vinyl, and/or cut resistant) to protect yourself from fluid", "2. Using tongs or a grabber, pick up needle by the middle of the plastic tube (syringe) with", "3. If there are multiple needles, pick them up one at a time.", "4. Place the needle-sharp end first into a puncture proof, sharps container. Keep the", "5. Return the sharps container to the proper storage location."]}, {"id": "substance", "title": "Substance Policy", "start": 48, "end": 50, "category": "Fitness for Duty", "text": "No. H&S - 001\n\nHEALTH & SAFETY POLICY Effective Date December 19, 2019\nSubstance Policy Revision 2019.1\n\n1.0 Purpose\n\nThe Essex Terminal Railway, including its associated companies, (herein “ETR”) is\ncommitted to the health and safety of its employees, the public and the environment.\n\nAs part of this commitment, ETR, its employees and unions, share a responsibility to\nmaintain a safe workplace, free from the negative effects of alcohol and other drugs. As\nsuch, ETR has zero tolerance for impairment in the workplace.\n\nManagement, unions and employees should be concerned with alcohol and other drug use\nbecause it can affect the health, safety, performance and conduct of employees on the job,\nand impose hardships on the employer, employee, co-workers and family and the\ncommunity at large. This policy is an important component of ETR’s program to minimize\nrisk in all operations and provides a framework for education, assistance, rehabilitation and\nreintegration of employees who have problems with substance abuse.\n\n2.0 Scope\n\nThis policy applies to all full-time and part-time employees and contractors of the ETR.\nThose employees in safety sensitive positions are held to a higher standard and are subject\nto more serious consequences because of the direct impact that their positions have on\nsafety.\n\n3.0 Policy\n3.01\n\nAll employees are required to report and remain fit for duty, free of the negative effects\nof alcohol, cannabis and other drugs which may impair their ability to safely perform\nthe essential duties of their job. It is strictly prohibited to be on duty or to be in control\nof an ETR vehicle or equipment while under the influence of alcohol or other drugs,\nincluding the after-effects of such use. Specifically, the use, consumption, possession,\ndistribution or sale of illegal drugs, cannabis or alcohol while on duty (including during\nbreaks), on or off company premises, in company vehicles and equipment, or while on\ncompany business, is strictly prohibited.\n\n3.02 Employees are expected to use over-the-counter, prescription or medically-authorized\ndrugs responsibly. All employees, in particular those in safety-sensitive positions or who\ncan be in control of ETR vehicles or equipment, are responsible for investigating whether\n\nthe medication may cause impairment. Employees must check with their own physician\nor pharmacist regarding the use of opiates, medically authorized cannabis, or any other\nimpairing medications, and report any concerns to your Supervisor and abide by their\nrecommendations to ensure safety.\n\n3.03 Employees who work or transfer into safety-sensitive or safety-critical positions are\nrequired to undergo pre-placement and/or periodic medical assessments that evaluate the\nimpact, if any, of medical conditions on fitness for work. As part of these assessments,\nhealth conditions such as substance use disorders and/or the use of impairing medication\ncan be identified, assessed and monitored, through the medical assessment and biological\ntesting (including drug testing). Where an employee in a safety sensitive or safety critical\nposition is diagnosed as having a substance use disorder, medical monitoring, including\ndrug and alcohol testing, may be required to ensure ongoing fitness for duty in this\nposition.\n\n3.04 Employees who work in safety sensitive positions may be subject to biological testing\nfor the presence of drugs in urine and oral fluids or a breathalyser where reasonable cause\nexists to suspect alcohol or drug use or possession in violation of this policy, including\nafter any significant accident or incident where an experienced operating officer, upon\nconsideration of the circumstances, determines that the cause may involve a violation of\na C.R.O.R. rule or company policy and/or impaired judgement by the employee. In cases\nof reasonable cause or post-accident testing, any employee whose breath alcohol\nconcentration is over 0.04, and/or who tests positive for legal or illegal drugs (without\nmedical justification) in oral fluids, and/or where impairment is demonstrated, will be\nconsidered to be in violation of this policy.\n\nEmployees may be monitored on the compliance of this policy, including testing for\ndrugs and alcohol, as part of their employment contract. This would be established as a\ncondition of continuing employment or reinstatement after dismissal.\n\n3.06 Employees who operate vehicles (whether company or customer) on public roadways\nmust possess the applicable provincial driver’s license with a clear driver’s abstract.\nEmployees are strictly prohibited from operating any ETR or customer vehicle and\nequipment while impaired.\n\nEmployees who require a valid driver’s license in the performance of their duties or who\noperate railway equipment and whose driving privileges are lost or suspended due to\nimpaired driving while not on duty, nor in an ETR vehicle, nor on ETR premises, must\nimmediately report such loss to their supervisor. A medical assessment will then\ndetermine whether the employee suffers from a substance use disorder.\n\n3.07 Employees found on company premises or in customer or ETR vehicles or equipment to\nbe possessing, distributing and/or selling substances, whether legal or illegal, which have\nthe potential to cause impairment will be terminated with cause. Employees may be\nsubject to contact from local authorities pertaining to violation incidents that transpire in\nthe workplace.\n\n3.08 Violation of this policy by any employee will result in discipline up to and including\ntermination of employment. Violation by contractors will be considered a breach of their\n\ncontract and will be dealt with accordingly. Refusal without cause to complete the testing\nprocess set out under this policy is considered a policy violation.\n\n3.09 ETR reserves the right to conduct unannounced searches for alcohol or drugs where there\nare reasonable grounds to believe they are present on premises, in vehicles and/or\nequipment owned, leased, or otherwise controlled by ETR, in contravention of this\npolicy.\n\n3.10 Where applicable, this policy supplements, but does not modify the Canadian Rail\nOperating Rules (C.R.O.R) Rule G. Nothing in this policy reduces the requirements of\nRule G.\n\n4.0 Responsibility\n4.01 Employees are responsible for arriving to work fit and free from impairment. If an\nemployee witnesses another employee who may be impaired, they should report it to\ntheir Supervisor immediately, consistent with their shared obligations as set out at Article\n1 above to ensure a safe workplace.\n\n4.02 Employees are to notify their Supervisor if they are prescribed a medication that may\ncause impairment. Human Resources will provide the necessary functional abilities form\nand job description to the Employee to give to the medical practitioner for completion.\nThe employee’s medical practitioner is expected to respond within a reasonable\ntimeframe in order to ensure appropriate accommodation may be reviewed and discussed\nwith the employee.\n\nIn situations where an employee has demonstrated a need for an accommodation, the\nemployee and his or her immediate Supervisor, with Human Resources support, are\nresponsible for working together in order to find a reasonable accommodation and\ndeveloping an accommodation plan, where necessary, in accordance with the Company’s\nAccident Investigation Procedures and applicable Human Rights and Occupational\nHealth and Safety legislation.\n\n4.03 Supervisors will be trained as to their responsibilities in administering this policy and are\nresponsible for delegating work assignments to their employees. If there is reason to\nbelieve that an employee may be suffering from an impairment the Supervisor should\nnotify their Manager immediately. A confidential conversation should take place with\nthe employee with Human Resources present.\n\n4.03 The President, Vice Presidents, Human Resources and Department Managers are jointly\nresponsible to develop and implement information, education, testing and follow-up\nrequired under this policy.\n\n5.0 Review\n5.01 This Policy will be reviewed on an annual basis.", "takeaways": ["HEALTH & SAFETY POLICY Effective Date December 19, 2019", "The Essex Terminal Railway, including its associated companies, (herein “ETR”) is", "committed to the health and safety of its employees, the public and the environment.", "As part of this commitment, ETR, its employees and unions, share a responsibility to"]}, {"id": "terminal", "title": "Terminal Expectations", "start": 51, "end": 51, "category": "Conduct", "text": "Terminal Expectations\n\nThis list of terminal expectations is designed to provide clarity of responsibilities for all team members\nat Essex Terminal Railway.\n\n1. All team members shall inspect and clean their work area/equipment/vehicle prior to end of their regular\nshift.\n2. No visiting, loitering, or sleeping during work hours.\n3. No leaving work during working hours without permission of your supervisor and/or failure to punch out\nprior to leaving the premises.\n4. Smoking is strictly prohibited in the buildings or work vehicles. Smoking is permitted only in designated\narea.\n5. All team members shall report any hazards to their manager/supervisor.\n6. Posting, distributing or removal of notices, signs or writing in any form on any bulletin boards or company\nproperty without permission from management is prohibited.\n7. All team members are expected to turn in any work-related reports, inspections as required.\n8. All team members shall comply with all communicated Health and Safety policies and procedures.\n9. All team members shall operate all work vehicles/equipment in a safe manner at all times.\n10. No use of ear buds or headphones where such use could cause distractions or be considered as a safety\nhazard.\n11. Use of personal cell phones is prohibited during work time.\n12. Cameras and digital recording devices are always prohibited in the workplace.\n13. Fighting or horseplay on the premises is not permitted. Throwing things or any actions, which may cause\ndistraction resulting in injury to an employee.\n14. Neglect, mishandling or deliberate destruction of machinery, equipment, or any Company property. You\nmust notify your supervisor of any damaged equipment.\n15. Failure to immediately report an accident, incident, near miss or injury to Supervisor.\n16. Removal of any material or property from premises without receiving proper authorization.\n17. Unauthorized use of Company telephone for personal business and/or long-distance calls.\n18. Unauthorized use of Company computers or any electronic devices for personal use.\n19. Possession of or being under the influence of alcohol on Company premises at any time. Possession of or\nbeing under the influence of any illegal or non-medically prescribed drugs/narcotics on Company premises\nor property, including the selling of any drug or narcotic, legal or illegal, prescribed or not to any person on\ncompany premises or property including the parking areas is prohibited.\n20. Falsifying or permitting falsification of information to the WSIB claims, medical forms, illnesses, or absences,\nshort disability claims, etc.\n21. Immoral conduct or indecency on Company property.\n22. Possession or use of weapons on Company property.\n23. Setting off fire alarm system or causing false fire alarms or tampering with protection equipment.\n24. Threatening, intimidating, harassing, bullying, or coercing fellow employees at any time for any purpose.\n25. All vehicles (personal/company) must be backed into parking spots where applicable. Driving away\nfrom a parked position must always be a forward movement.\n\nNon-compliance of these expectations will result in appropriate disciplinary action, up to and\nincluding termination. Management will determine the level of discipline after review of the\ncircumstances of the incident, prior disciplinary record, and other relevant factors. The Company\nreserves sole and exclusive right to amend these expectations from time to time.", "takeaways": ["1. All team members shall inspect and clean their work area/equipment/vehicle prior to end of their regular", "2. No visiting, loitering, or sleeping during work hours.", "3. No leaving work during working hours without permission of your supervisor and/or failure to punch out", "4. Smoking is strictly prohibited in the buildings or work vehicles. Smoking is permitted only in designated", "5. All team members shall report any hazards to their manager/supervisor."]}, {"id": "smoke", "title": "Smoke and Vape Free Workplace", "start": 52, "end": 53, "category": "Conduct", "text": "SMOKE AND VAPE FREE WORKPLACE POLICY\n\nPURPOSE\n\nThe Essex Terminal Railway is committed to providing a healthy, comfortable and productive work\nenvironment for our employees and everyone visiting our premises.\n\nIn order to eliminate hazards and ensure a safe, healthy workplace we have established designated\nsmoking/vaping areas. All employees must be aware of all acceptable designated areas.\n\nRESPONSIBILITY\n\nAll forms of tobacco use including the use of electronic nicotine delivery systems – known as vapes\nor e-cigarettes, will be strictly prohibited within company buildings.\n\nAll company vehicles, locomotives and equipment will be designated smoke/vape-free, including\nrental vehicles or equipment used for company business.\n\nThe success of this policy will depend on the thoughtfulness, consideration and cooperation of\nsmokers and non-smokers. All of us share in the responsibility for adhering to and enforcing this\npolicy.\n\nConforming to this policy will make our company compliant with provincial legislation, The Smoke-\nfree Ontario Act.\n\nCopies of this policy will be made available to all employees. Signs will be posted at all building\nentrances. Failure to adhere to this policy will result in disciplinary action up to and including\ntermination of employment.\n\nHEALTH AND\nSAFETY\nPOLICIES AND\nPROCEDURES", "takeaways": ["The Essex Terminal Railway is committed to providing a healthy, comfortable and productive work", "environment for our employees and everyone visiting our premises.", "In order to eliminate hazards and ensure a safe, healthy workplace we have established designated", "smoking/vaping areas. All employees must be aware of all acceptable designated areas."]}, {"id": "emergency", "title": "ETR Emergency Plan Procedures", "start": 54, "end": 62, "category": "Emergency Response", "text": "No. ETR - H&S - 013\n\nHEALTH & SAFETY PROCEDURE Effective April 25,2025\nDate\nETR Emergency Plan Procedure (Railway) Revision 2025.3\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\n\nIt is the policy of Essex Terminal Railway to ensure and require, that a plan and procedures\nare developed, implemented, and maintained to effectively deal with Emergency situations that\nmay occur at the workplace. These measures are developed to carry out the overall objectives\nof the Emergency Plan, in order of priority:\n\n*To reduce the risk of death or injury resulting from emergency situations.\n*To provide for the safety, care, and comfort of personnel.\n*To reduce and minimize damage to property, equipment, and inventory.\n*To accelerate the resumption of normal operations.\n1.0 Scope:\nETR’s emergency plan procedure applies to all employees, contractors, vendors,\ncontract workers, customers and visitors.\n\nThese measures apply to, but are not limited to:\na) Serious Workplace Accident, Illness, Rescues and Entrapment.\nb) Explosions\nc) Bomb Threats\nd) Major Storms/Severe Weather\ne) Fire\nf) Natural Gas Leak\ng) Chemical Spill\nh) Power Failure\ni) Crime Prevention\nj) Workplace Violence\nk) Water Supply Interruption\nl) Propane Emergencies\n2.0 Responsibilities:\n\nEMERGENCY COORDINATOR - The overall responsibility and authority to administer the\nEmergency Plan is the responsibility of the EMERGENCY COORDINATOR. The\nresponsibilities of the EMERGENCY COORDINATOR will be as follows:\n\nDAY SHIFT – SUPERINTENDENT (Assistant Superintendent- If Superintendent\nnot available)\n\nAFTERNOON SHIFT – TRAINMASTER / YARD COORDINATOR (where\napplicable if Trainmaster unavailable)\n\nMIDNIGHT SHIFT (IF APPLICABLE) – SUPERINTENDENT / ASSISTANT\nSUPERINTENDENT / TRAINMASTER\n\nEMERGENCY COORDINATOR RESPONSIBILITIES\n\nIt is the responsibility of the EMERGENCY COORDINATOR (or designate), and\nthat person has the authority to:\n• Communicate with and notify the appropriate outside agencies to deal\nwith and respond to emergency situations (e.g., fire and police\ndepartments., ambulance, etc.)\n• Assess the situation to determine whether it is necessary to activate\nemergency procedures, including site wide or partial evacuations.\n• Designate team members and assign responsibility for emergency\noperations in given areas.\n• Notify senior management (Director of Operations/VP/President) and\nkeep them informed of the status of the emergency. During afternoon or\nmidnight shift operations, the Emergency Coordinator, where practical,\nwill ensure prompt notification is communicated to the off-site\n(Superintendent).\n\nSUPERINTENDENT, ASSISTANT SUPERINTENDENT, TRAINMASTER\n\nIt is the responsibility of these Managers/Supervisors:\n\n• To ensure each worker under their supervision is familiar with the\nEmergency Plan and its required actions.\n• To ensure each worker under their supervision is instructed as to the\nlocation of emergency exits, evacuation routes and evacuation\nassembly area.\n• To account for each worker under their supervision and report this\ninformation to the Emergency Coordinator if an evacuation is required.\nWORKERS\n\nIt is the responsibility of each Worker:\n\n• To report to their immediate Supervisor, or any available\nManager/Supervisor, the conditions or circumstances that exist or\nmay lead to the existence of emergency situations.\n• If designated, trained in the use and application of first aid, C.P.R.,\nartificial respiration or fire-fighting techniques, to respond to and\nprovide assistance in emergency situations under the direction of the\nEmergency Coordinator (or designate).\n• Where applicable, to evacuate the site/building by the closest and\nsafest exit in an orderly fashion upon direction of a Supervisor or\nhearing the designated emergency signal.\n• To report directly to the appropriate evacuation assembly area\nfollowing evacuation. This will ensure that employees can be\nefficiently accounted for.\n• To remain at the predetermined evacuation assembly area until further\ninstructions are given to them by their Supervisors/Managers\n\nCONTRACTORS, VENDORS, CONTRACT WORKERS, CUSTOMERS, VISITORS\n\n• Any visitor to any location, whether contractor, vendor, contract\nworker, consultant or customer will be advised of emergency\n\nevacuation plan by the company representative they are visiting.\nAccounting for visitors in an emergency will be the responsibility of the\ncompany representative they are visiting.\n3.0 Definitions:\n\nEVACUATION ASSEMBLY AREA: The evacuation assembly area is the external area that\npersonnel will report to upon being directed to evacuate part or all of the site or buildings.\n\nETR RAILWAY: All employees must report to the evacuation assembly area, located approx.\n200' north-east of the Engine house in the cut out.\n\nALARM NOTIFICATION SIGNAL FOR EMERGENCIES:\n\nETR: All staff shall be informed of the Fire alarm button on the keypads located by all\nmain doors. This will activate the audible sound on site and security one will receive\nnotification of this alarm. Employees will also be advised verbally by members of\nsupervision (or designates) either directly or by handheld radios (where available).\n\nMAPS/FLOOR PLANS: Maps and floor plans are posted and available to illustrate the\nTERMINAL LAYOUT and identifying:\n* Emergency Exits\n* Evacuation Assembly Area\n* Inclement Weather Assembly Area\n* Fire Extinguishers\n* First-Aid Stations/Rooms\n\nTRAINING & INSTRUCTION: All employees shall be trained in the provisions of this plan.\nAll training shall be documented.\n\n4.0 Procedure:\n\n4.1 SERIOUS ACCIDENT / ILLNESS / RESCUE & ENTRAPMENT\n\n1. The first person on the scene must assess the situation, determine\nif additional assistance is required, and where appropriate, initiate\nFirst-Aid or C.P.R. (if trained and authorized).\n2. Under no circumstances should equipment, materials, etc. be moved\nor operated until the injured person is stabilized or unless it is\nnecessary to prevent further injury.\n3. A member of Supervisory/Management Staff must be notified as\nsoon as is practicable and will coordinate as the Emergency\nCoordinator at the scene.\n4. External required emergency services (ambulance, fire department,\npolice, etc.) shall be notified immediately following assessment of the\nstatus of the injured person and situation. This is the responsibility of\nthe on-site Supervisor/ Emergency Coordinator in consultation\nwith the first aid / C.P.R. attendant.\n5. If the Accident/Incident involves machinery or equipment\nEntanglement/Entrapment; on site staff with appropriate expertise\nshall be made available without delay. This is the responsibility of the\non-site Supervisor/Emergency Coordinator.\n6. The Supervisor/ Emergency Coordinator will appoint two (2)\npersons to direct external emergency services into the facility or\nappropriate area.\n7. Human Resources/Superintendant will notify the injured person's\nnext of kin only after:\n\nSTATUS OF THE SITUATION IS KNOWN and, the injured person's condition is known and\nstable, or the injured person is in the care and custody of emergency services and in transit\nto a medical facility.\n\n4.2 EXPLOSION\n\n1. Upon witnessing an explosion or the potential of an explosion an\nemployee shall notify the Supervisor immediately.\n2. Upon notification of an explosion or its potential, the Supervisor will\na) Remove local personnel from danger area\nb) Notify appropriate personnel\n3. The situation will be immediately assessed, and if required, activate\nthe evacuation signal, and designate an individual to contact the\nappropriate Emergency Service (Fire, Police, Ambulance) if\nnecessary.\n\n4.3 BOMB THREATS\n\n1. When a telephone threat is received, listen carefully, and obtain as\nmuch information as possible. Note the time. Information should be\ndocumented, if possible, during the telephone call. Ask the following\nquestions:\nWhere is the bomb, is there more than one?\nWhat time will it explode?\nWhat does it look like?\nWhy and how did you place the bomb?\nWho are you?\nWhen did you place the bomb?\n2. Attempt to keep the caller on the telephone and note the phone\nnumber indicated on the call display if applicable.\n\n3. As time permits, notification should be made to the Emergency\nCoordinator, during or immediately following the call.\n4. The Emergency Coordinator shall immediately be made aware of the\nsituation and notify senior management.\n5. The Emergency Coordinator, in consultation with senior management,\nshall notify the police and fire departments, and following their advice\nand direction shall:\n6. initiate partial or entire facility evacuation.\n\n4.4 MAJOR STORMS/SEVERE WEATHER\n\nThe most common impacts from storms and severe weather (i.e., heavy snow,\ntornadoes, thunderstorms) are as follows:\n• power failure.\n• damage to structures, roofing, and unsecured materials.\n• injury from blowing debris; and\n• vehicle accidents.\n\nThe Emergency Coordinator shall ensure that:\n\n1. Nonessential outdoor activities are discontinued as per any internal\nprocedures at each terminal. Ensure contact with any employee working\noutside or off-site and have all employees report to the designated\ninclement weather assembly area immediately, if safe to do so and time\npermits.\n2. Offsite employees may not be able to return, so Supervisors should try to\nconfirm the location of all workers.\n3. Secure loose materials outdoors, and building openings (doors, vents,\nwindows, etc.) as appropriate.\n4. In the event of water leakage or damage, electrical power should be\ndisconnected, where appropriate.\n\nIn the event of a tornado warning or an actual sighting, the employee seeing or hearing of\na tornado in the area will:\n\n1. Notify the Supervisor.\n2. Upon notification the Supervisor/ Emergency\nCoordinator should advise a member of senior\nmanagement if time permits.\n3. The situation shall be quickly assessed, and notification\nsounded for the employees to gather at the designated\ninclement weather assembly area location at each\nfacility.\n4. Ideal designated locations should be: In any lower-\nlevel interior room, without windows. Cemented\nwalled areas most preferred. Please ensure all\nemployees are made aware of each Terminal’s meeting\narea.\n\nETR RAILWAY: All employees on site must report to the Engine House first aid room.\n\nOnce the employees are in their designated locations, everyone should get as close to the\nground as they can and stay as far away from windows as possible. Always protect your head\nby covering it or going under large, heavy pieces of furniture.\n\nThe Supervisors present should ensure that all employees remain in these locations until the\n\ndanger has passed. After the danger has passed the employees must be advised to return to\ntheir work areas if applicable.\n\n4.5 FIRE\n\n1. Upon discovering a fire an employee shall notify his/her Supervisor.\n2. Upon notification of a fire the Supervisor will:\n3. Immediately proceed to the location of the fire and take charge. He/she shall\ndetermine the course of action to be taken by assessing the situation in the\nfollowing sequence:\n4. Remove local personnel from danger areas and assess whether an evacuation\nof the area or building is required.\n5. Attempt to extinguish the fire if trained and confident to perform.\n6. Determine whether the Fire Department should be called.\n7. Have a person in the area notify the Site Manager or the Emergency\nCoordinator.\n8. If a full evacuation is required, one (1) individual shall be designated to activate\nthe evacuation notification. See Evacuation procedure below for details. The\nEmergency Coordinator (or designate) will ensure the SDS book is obtained\nto give to the Fire Department.\n9. If the Fire Department is required, the Supervisor or a designated person\nshall call the Fire Department and then send a guide to the facility entrance.\n10. Each Supervisor shall endeavor to control the fire with the use of the proper\nequipment if safe to do so, until the arrival of the Fire Department. They will\ngive the Fire Department as much assistance as required without endangering\ntheir own life or the life of any other company personnel at the scene.\n11. All precautions should be taken to minimize the danger to any ETR employee.\n\n4.6 NATURAL GAS LEAK\n\n1. Upon discovery of a gas leak or damaged equipment that could cause a gas\nto leak an employee shall notify a Supervisor.\n2. The Supervisor shall contact the Gas Company (listed with Emergency Phone\nList) and proceed with the instructions given.\n3. If a full evacuation is required, the normal procedure will be followed.\n\n4.7 OIL/COOLANT & CHEMICAL SPILL RESPONSE\n\n1. On the discovery of a spill, employees shall immediately notify a supervisor.\n2. Upon notification of a spill the Supervisor will immediately proceed to the\nlocation of the spill and take charge. He/she shall determine the course of\naction to be taken by assessing the situation in the following sequence:\n3. Remove local personnel from danger area and assess whether an evacuation\nof the area or building is required.\n4. Immediately contain the spill utilizing the Spill Response Kit.\n5. Arrange to have an Environmental Service Provider safely cleanup and\ntransport the spill (if required) as outlined below.\n• Oil/Coolant Spills of LESS THAN 100L should be contained and cleaned\nup internally. The use of absorbable socks and pads should be used to\ncleanup spills.\n• Spills of MORE THAN 100L should be contained and cleaned up by an\nEnvironmental Service Provider.\n• Spills of Hazardous Chemicals should be contained and cleaned up by an\nEnvironmental Service Provider.\n\nSpills that can cause, or are likely to cause the following, must be reported immediately\nto the Spills Action Centre of the Ministry of Environment and the City of Windsor (See\nEmergency Telephone List):\n• Impairment to the quality of the natural environment – air, water, or land.\n• Injury or damage to property or animal life.\n• Adverse health effects to any person\n• Making property, facilities, or animal life unfit for use.\n\nIf a full evacuation is required, one (1) individual shall be designated to activate the\nevacuation notification system. See Evacuation procedure for details.\nAn investigation/response report will be completed for all reportable spills at any facility\nor property.\n\n4.8 POWER FAILURE\n\n1. In the event of a power failure, employees are to remain at their current location\nuntil receiving further instructions from a supervisor.\n2. The Emergency Coordinator will determine the source of the power failure\nand estimated length. In the event of an estimated power blackout spanning\ndifferent shifts, the Emergency Coordinator will arrange to contact the\nemployees being affected.\n\n4.9 CRIME PREVENTION/ ACTIVE SHOOTER\nIf you witness an incident involving an active shooter outside the building:\n• Stay out of sight (away from windows) and warn colleagues, clients,\nand visitors.\n• Leave the area at risk.\n• When safe to do so, call 911, and other building occupants.\n• If you cannot evacuate the building safely, lock outside doors and\nclose the blinds and curtains.\n• Wait for instructions from first responders.\n\nIf you witness an incident involving an active shooter inside the building:\n• Stay calm.\n• If you can do so safely, leave the area immediately.\n• Warn others, as many as possible, without attracting the attention of\nthe assailant\n• If you can do so safely, call 911 and notify other building occupants.\n• Lock the doors or barricade yourself in a room using furniture.\n• Block the windows, close the office blinds and curtains.\n• If the workplace has no door, hide under your desk or where you\ncannot be seen.\n• If you are in a washroom, remain there, if safe to do so.\n• Silence your cellphone, turn off radios and computers.\n• If you cannot escape, remain silent and hide until the first responders\narrive.\n• Wait for instructions from first responders.\n\n4.10 WORKPLACE VIOLENCE\n\nIf you witness or experience violence at work:\n• Remove yourself from the situation if you can.\n• Inform your manager or seek help from a co-worker immediately.\n• If your manager is the perpetrator, notify another manager in the line\n\nof authority.\n• If your physical security or well-being is threatened contact your\nSupervisor, or contact yard office (railway) immediately for assistance\n\nIf you are dealing with a violent person:\n• Stay calm.\n• Try to calm the other person or diffuse the situation (if you can).\n• Avoid saying or doing anything that could aggravate the situation.\n• Avoid eye contact or sudden movements that can be perceived as\nthreatening.\n• Respect the person’s personal space.\n• Continue the conversation with the person only if the person calms\ndown.\n• Tell the person that you understand the reason for their anger.\n• If the behavior persists, end the conversation.\n• Politely notify the person that you will leave the work area or ask them\nto do so.\n• Notify your supervisor or seek help from a co-worker or anyone in the\n• direct area immediately.\n\n4.11 WATER SUPPLY INTERRUPTION\n\n1. If the water supply is interrupted, the Emergency Coordinator will contact the\nwater supplier (See Emergency Phone List) to determine the anticipated length\nof the interruption.\n2. For short periods of interruption, arrangements should be made to ensure that\nhand sanitizer and bottled water for manual flushing of toilets is available in\nthe washrooms.\n3. If the interruption is anticipated to be longer than 8 hours, arrangements should\nbe made to have portable toilets delivered to the facility.\n\n4.12 PROPANE EMERGENCIES:\n\n1. In the event of fire, use water to cool exposed cylinders or tanks, if safe to do\nso.\n2. Immediately clear the area.\n3. Depending on the situation (determined by Management) call the propane\nsupplier for assistance or, where warranted, call 911.\n4. If necessary, have a qualified technician inspect or address any possible leaks.\n\n5.0 Safety Information:\n\nEVACUATION PROCEDURE\n\nAll Personnel\n1. The designated employee on duty at the ETR Rail Office will initiate their alarm\nsignal on the key pads.\n2. Upon hearing the evacuation signal, shut down any equipment under your\ncontrol and exit the building/area in an orderly fashion and meet at your", "takeaways": ["Communicate with and notify the appropriate outside agencies to deal", "Assess the situation to determine whether it is necessary to activate", "Designate team members and assign responsibility for emergency", "Notify senior management (Director of Operations/VP/President) and", "To ensure each worker under their supervision is familiar with the"]}, {"id": "inspection", "title": "Workplace Inspection and Housekeeping", "start": 63, "end": 65, "category": "Hazard Control", "text": "facility’s Evacuation Assembly Area.\n3. Report to your Supervisor upon arriving at the evacuation assembly area.\n4. Do not leave the evacuation assembly area until directed by your supervisor.\n5. Do not re-enter the building until instructed by your supervisor.\n6. Supervisors will ensure that their work areas are evacuated of workers and\nvisitors, and that all employees, visitors or contractors are accounted for by\nperforming a roll call.\n\nSupervisors, Managers, Emergency Coordinators\n\n1. Ensure that all employees and visitors have left their work area.\n2. Ensure the fire alarm button on the security keypad in the office (if safe to do\nso), is pushed to automatically alert our security Company who will also alert\nproper authorities.\n3. Telephone 911 operator and give details regarding the emergency and ask for\nthe proper authorities.\n4. Account for all employees and visitors (headcount) at the evacuation assembly\narea. Ensure you have an up-to-date daily shift list to account for everyone.\nKnow if there are visitors or contractors on site that need to be accounted for.\n5. Do not allow anyone back into the building until instructed by the assigned\nEmergency Coordinator and/or Emergency Services (Fire Dept.).\n\nNo. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-020\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 3-June-2025\nWORKPLACE INSPECTION and HOUSEKEEPING Revision 2025.1\nPROGRAM\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to ensuring the health and safety of everyone in the workplace. It recognizes\nthe importance of workers and employers working together to identify and resolve health and\nsafety issues in the workplace. ETR is committed to complying with applicable legislation by\nmaintaining a tidy workplace and conducting workplace inspections (audits) at regular intervals,\nto ensure a workplace that is safe and free of hazards that could contribute to workplace\nincidents or injuries.\n\nPROCEDURE\nWORKPLACE INSPECTIONS\n\nRegular JHSC/WC workplace inspection schedule will be documented and posted in a\nconspicuous location in the workplace. Inspections of each work area are to be completed on a\nmonthly basis or at least part of the workplace completed monthly. The purpose of the\ninspections is to identify potential and actual hazards in order to eliminate/control at the\nsource. Following every workplace inspection, the worker conducting the inspection shall sign\nand submit to management a completed Workplace Inspection Checklist.\nInspections and follow up to inspections can:\n\n• Prevent incidents.\n• Detect wear, tear or potential failure of equipment, tools, or materials.\n• Prevent damage to property, equipment, and material.\n• Ensure that there is no equipment misuse.\n• Improve housekeeping standards.\n• Eliminate or minimize any fire hazard.\n• Protect the integrity of the environment\n\nSUPERVISORS AND MANAGERS\nSupervisors/Managers shall conduct daily inspections/audits of their worksites as part of their\nnormal work routine. These inspections shall be conducted prior to assigning tasks to team\nmembers and periodically throughout the day.\nPurpose of inspections:\n\n• Recognize hazards and take corrective actions applicable in the circumstances. Collaborate\nwith the JHSC/WC for recommendations.\n• Communicate the potential and actual hazards to the workers\n• Continual monitoring of critical parts and equipment performance.\n• Identify maintenance and repair work when required.\n• Identify gaps in policies/procedures such as documented equipment inspections (forklifts,\ncranes, etc.)\n• Eliminate/Control housekeeping hazards that may lead to slip, trip hazards.\n\n• To promote a positive safety culture by communicating a proactive approach to Health and\nSafety.\n\nWORKERS\n• Shall be provided with time prior to end of shift to clean up their work areas.\n• Shall conduct inspections of equipment as required by legislation and ETR policies.\n• Are expected to support this policy/procedure in order to eliminate/control hazards that are\ncreated by poor housekeeping.\n\nINSPECTION PROCEDURES\nWhen performing a planned JHSC/WC inspection:\n\n• Cover the work area systematically, inspecting one item at a time.\n• Look for items in out of the way places, which might be missed in the daily walk around.\n• Reference equipment/worksite checklists and/or safe operating procedures to ensure\nthat all items are covered.\n• Complete the inspection using the workplace specific checklist.\n• Clearly describe and identify the location of each deficiency using established names\nand markings. (take pictures if authorized to carry phone)\n• Record damaged or malfunctioning equipment or material.\n• Record inadequate or incorrect work procedures.\n• Record unnecessary items, such as unused material or equipment.\n• Note cluttered and poorly arranged areas (poor housekeeping).\nIf, during the inspection, equipment is discovered that poses a serious health and safety risk or is\nidentified as non-compliant then the equipment must be removed from service. Ensure the\ninspection report contains a record of the corrective actions taken (notes, text/call to Supervisor\netc.) for all identified hazards prior to the inspection report being filed.\n\nWORK EQUIPMENT AND SAFETY EQUIPMENT\nAll work and safety equipment will be identified and inventoried. All workers must follow\nmanufacturers’ specifications and maintenance and inspection protocols required by OHSA, CLC,\nRegulations, standards and codes for all vehicles, machinery, tools, equipment, and fire safety\nequipment.\n\nHOUSEKEEPING\nETR is committed to maintaining a tidy workplace. As such, ETR shall ensure that its workplace is\ncleaned regularly. ETR shall provide time at the end of each work day for general clean-up by\nemployees, of their work areas. ETR will either assign team members internally to perform\nregular housekeeping duties, or alternatively, hire a third-party to perform cleaning services.\nETR shall set a regular cleaning schedule.", "takeaways": ["3. Report to your Supervisor upon arriving at the evacuation assembly area.", "4. Do not leave the evacuation assembly area until directed by your supervisor.", "5. Do not re-enter the building until instructed by your supervisor.", "6. Supervisors will ensure that their work areas are evacuated of workers and", "1. Ensure that all employees and visitors have left their work area."]}, {"id": "first-aid", "title": "First Aid Policy and Procedure", "start": 66, "end": 69, "category": "Emergency Response", "text": "YEARLY REVIEW\n\nETR in conjunction with JHSC/WC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual basis or\nmore often if necessary.\n\nNo. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-024\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 13-May-2025\nFIRST AID POLICY AND PROCEDURE Revision 2025.1\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\n\nETR is committed to ensuring the health, safety and well-being of everyone in the workplace by\nprotecting and enhancing a positive encompassing culture through the creation of a First Aid\nprocedure to ensure timely and effective care after an injury or reported exposure. ETR\nrecognizes the importance of ensuring that all identified parties understand and follow\napplicable legislation to support the workplace.\n\nSCOPE\nETR shall at all times maintain the minimum number of first aiders and first aid supplies based\non the applicable worker count, types of hazards in the workplace and travel distance to a\nhospital or other professional medical services.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\nEmployer\n• Ensure that the employer’s commitment to provide first aid equipment, services and supplies\nare met.\n• Ensure written instructions are developed and implemented to address the first aid\nrequirements for summoning first aid, treating, and transporting of injured works.\n• Direct workers to report all injuries, industrial diseases, and illnesses.\n• Ensure first aid attendants have sufficient time to assess, treat, document, and follow up on\ninjured workers.\n• Shall ensure an appropriate number of first aid kits are available and easily accessible\nManagement/Supervisors\n• Instruct all workers on written procedures regarding who and how to call for first aid,\ntransportation of injured workers, and access/egress routes.\n• Assign responsibility to monitor and ensure first aid attendants maintain current first aid\ncertification at the workplace.\n• Assign responsibility to inspect monthly and restock first aid supplies as required\nWorkers\n• Immediately report all injuries, industrial illness, regardless of the extent or\ninjury, to a supervisor or first aid attendant.\n• Cooperate with First aid attendant and provide details of nature of injury\n\nFirst Aid Station and Personnel\n\nThe companies first aid boxes shall be maintained in good condition and shall be large enough\nso that each item is in plain view and easily accessible. Moreover, the expense of furnishing and\nmaintaining first aid appliances and services shall be the responsibility of the company.\nThe company shall post:\n• The Ontario Workplace Safety and Insurance Board’s “In Case of Injury” poster (Form 82).\n• The valid first aid certificates of qualification of the trained workers on duty; and\n\n• Ensure that its first aid boxes and their contents are checked regularly and are in good working\norder. Inspections shall be completed using the inspection forms provided.\nIn the event that a worker needs first aid treatment, use the First Aid Log book.\nThe company shall ensure that its first aid station is at, all times, in the charge of a worker who is\nthe holder of:\n\n• A valid St. John Ambulance Standard First Aid Certificate or its equivalent for workplaces\nwith more than 5 workers.\n• Works in the immediate vicinity of the first aid box.\nNALOXONE KITS\nIf the company becomes aware, or ought reasonably to be aware, that there may be a risk of a\nworker having an opioid overdose at a workplace where that worker performs work for the\nemployer, or where the prescribed circumstances exist, the employer shall, provide and\nmaintain a Naloxone kit.\nThe kit must be kept in the vicinity of a worker who has received the required training and at\nany time workers are present in the workplace. The Naloxone Kit must be stored at room\ntemperature (15C to 25C), kept in the kit until ready for use and protected from light.\nThe names and workplace locations of workers who are in charge of the naloxone kit and have\nreceived training will be posted in a conspicuous location closest to the kits.\n\nProcedure\nWhen an injury or health related issue occurs:\n1. Injured worker or nearby co-worker shall notify supervisor immediately, an injury has\noccurred.\n2. If injured worker is able to proceed to nearest first aid station, supervisor shall ensure a\ncertified first aid attendant is available to assess and treat the injured worker.\n3. If injured worker is unable to relocate, first aid attendant shall come to him/her.\n4. First aid shall be provided by certified first aider based on injuries/illness.\n5. Initial assessment shall determine the need or not for external medical care.\n6. If assessment determines standard first aid is applicable, first aid shall be administered.\n7. First aid attendant together with injured worker shall fill out the first aid log book\n8. Discuss returning back to work with the worker and supervisor, reassess injury after a period\nof time where applicable.\n9. If external medical care is required, supervisor shall arrange for safe transportation to\nhospital or clinic.\n10. Supervisors shall conduct an investigation based on the circumstances and fill out an\naccident/incident investigation form.\n11. All applicable information shall be reviewed and signed off by each terminals Manager and\nthen submitted to HR and Corporate Health and Safety Specialist.\nFor the purposes of this Policy, and subject to applicable legislation, the following shall be\ndeemed to be a workplace\n\n1. A railway train, vessel on which a worker is employed.\n2. A vehicle being used by an employer to transport workers; or\n3. A vehicle used by employees to carry out their duties as an employee.\nFIRST AID RECORDS\nThe company shall maintain at the workplace a record of all injuries and exposures to\ncontaminants that are reported or treated.\n• First aid records must be kept for at least 3 years.\n• The first aid records do not identify the worker, or\n• Workers may request or authorize access to their first aid records for any treatment or report\nabout themselves.\nThe companies HR department shall keep the first aid records, to respect worker privacy as per\nlegislation and has limited access to first aid records. The first aid records must be kept private,\nand that no person other than the worker has access to their first aid records.\nThe only exceptions to the privacy and security requirements are:\n• An inspector requires the production of the first aid records for purposes of inspection.\n• The first aid records do not identify the worker; or\n• The worker has given written consent to disclose their first aid records.\n\nFIRST AID KIT INSPECTIONS\nThe company shall ensure that its first aid boxes and their contents are checked monthly, to\nensure that they are fully stocked as prescribed. Inspections shall be completed using the First\nAid Inventory Form.\n\nYEARLY REVIEW\n\nThe company in conjunction with JHSC/WC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual\nbasis or more often if necessary.\n\nDefinitions:\n“worker” means any of the following, but does not include an inmate of a correctional institution\nor like institution or facility who participates inside the institution or facility in a work project or\nrehabilitation program:\n\n1. A person who performs work or supplies services for monetary compensation.\n2. A secondary school student who performs work or supplies services for no monetary\ncompensation under a work experience program authorized by the school board that operates\nthe school in which the student is enrolled.", "takeaways": ["Ensure that the employer’s commitment to provide first aid equipment, services and supplies", "Ensure written instructions are developed and implemented to address the first aid", "Direct workers to report all injuries, industrial diseases, and illnesses.", "Ensure first aid attendants have sufficient time to assess, treat, document, and follow up on", "Shall ensure an appropriate number of first aid kits are available and easily accessible"]}, {"id": "whmis", "title": "WHMIS 2015 Policy and Program", "start": 70, "end": 73, "category": "Hazard Control", "text": "3. A person who performs work or supplies services for no monetary compensation under a\nprogram approved by a college of applied arts and technology, university, career college or\nother post-secondary institution.\n4. REPEALED: 2017, c. 22, Sched. 1, s. 71 (2).\n5. Such other persons as may be prescribed who perform work or supply services to an employer\nfor no monetary compensation.\n\n“workplace” means any land, premises, location or thing at, upon, in or near which a worker\nworks;\n\nNo. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-023\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 3-June-2025\nWHMIS 2015 POLICY AND PROGRAM Revision 2025.1\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to providing a safe environment for workers and visitors who work with or\naround hazardous materials. ETR shall take steps to ensure that materials described as\n\n“hazardous products” are identified and all persons in the workplace will be made aware of and\ntrained on the hazards specific to these products.\n\nSCOPE\nThis policy addresses the requirements of WHMIS 2015 and is intended to:\n\n• Educate workers on the potential health and safety hazards associated with\nusing, storing, handling, and disposing of hazardous products.\n• Prevent chemical-related accidents, incidents, injuries, and illnesses.\n• Ensure appropriate and accurate labelling and documentation of hazardous products in the\nworkplace.\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITES\nEmployers shall ensure:\n• Hazardous products and materials are used, handled, and stored in the manner as\nprescribed.\n• All hazardous products and materials are identified and labelled in the manner as\nprescribed.\n• Proper policies, procedures and protocols are in place to ensure that proper records and\ndata concerning hazardous products in the workplace are maintained.\n• All workers are trained in the use, handling, storage, and disposal of hazardous products and\nkeep records of training logs.\n• That an introduction of any new product or composition change of a current product that all\nemployees are notified and retrained on specific product.\n• Training needs are reviewed with the JHSC/WC on an annual basis.\n• Copies of all SDS are available to all workers and the JHSC/WC.\n• Copies of SDS are made available to regulatory authorities upon request.\n\nSupervisors shall:\n• Advise all employees of the location of SDS for hazardous products.\n• Advise all employees who may be exposed to hazardous products of the hazards of such\nproducts that may be present when used in the workplace.\n• Ensure appropriate WHMIS training is provided to all employees prior to assigning them to\nwork with hazardous products.\n• Communicate and enforce safe work procedures and personal protective equipment\nrequirements with workers.\n• Ensure that employees do not use hazardous products in the workplace until the SDS has\nbeen reviewed and appropriate measures are in place.\n• Produce workplace labels when required.\n• Perform routine inspections to ensure the requirements of this policy are met.\n\nWorkers shall:\n• Complete WHMIS 2015 training provided by the employer.\n\n• Adhere to safe work practices and procedures when working with hazardous products.\n• Refrain from using any hazardous products until SDS has been reviewed and appropriate\nmeasures have been put in place to minimize risk.\n• Report to supervisors any concerns about hazardous products in the workplace.\n\nJoint Health and Safety Committee/Workplace Committee shall:\n• During the monthly workplace inspections, verify that hazardous products are\nappropriately labelled and that SDS are up-to-date and readily available to all workers.\n• Annually, in consultation with management, review the WHMIS 2015 training program to\nensure compliance and applicability.\n\nTRAINING REQUIREMENTS\nAll employees shall be trained in all aspects of WHMIS 2015, but will not be limited to:\n\n• The content required to be on a supplier label and a workplace label and the purpose and\nsignificance of the information on the label.\n• Procedures for safely storing, using, and handling hazardous products.\n• Information on the contents (format) required on a Safety Data Sheet (SDS) and the purpose\nand significance of the information.\n• Where to obtain a copy of the SDS.\n• Procedures to be followed in case of an emergency involving a hazardous product.\n\nHANDLING PROCEDURES\nEveryone involved at ETR must follow required procedures under WHMIS and the Hazardous\nProducts Regulations (Canada).\n\nSupplier Labels\n• Individuals who supply hazardous products are required to apply a label that meets the\nrequirements of the Hazardous Products Regulations.\n• A supplier label has six sections in a set order and minimum information is prescribed.\nStandardized hazard statement, signal words and symbols will appear on the label according\nto the classification of that chemical or mixture. Precautionary statements may also be\nrequired.\n• No one shall alter a supplier label on a container containing hazardous products.\n• If the label applied to a hazardous product or a container of a hazardous product becomes\nillegible or is removed, the employer shall replace the label with either a supplier label or a\nworkplace label.\n• When significant new data is received by ETR about a hazardous product, ETR shall, as soon\nas possible, attach the new information to every relevant supplier label and ensure that\nemployees are trained.\n• Supplier labels must be in both official languages in Canada − English and French.\n\nWorkplace Labels\nA workplace label is required if:\n• a hazardous product is transferred or poured into another container; or\n• a supplier label is lost or illegible.\nA workplace label should contain:\n• the product name (which must match the SDS product name).\n• safe handling precautions (which may include pictogram or other supplier label\ninformation); and\n• a reference to the SDS.\n\nSafety Data Sheets (SDS)\nSafety Data Sheets (SDS) are summary documents that provide information about the hazards of\na product and advice about safety precautions. SDS are usually written by the manufacturer or\nsupplier of the product.\nSDS provides more detailed hazard information about the product than the label. They are an\nimportant resource for workers to help learn more about the product(s). Use this information to\nidentify the hazards of the products you use and to protect yourself from those hazards,\nincluding safe handling and emergency measures.\nSDS tells users what the hazards of the product are, how to use the product safely, what to\nexpect if the recommendations are not followed, how to recognize symptoms of exposure, and\nwhat to do if emergencies occur.\nSDS must be readily available for the JHSC/WC and to workers who are exposed to hazardous\nproducts.\nA supplier will provide the SDS, in English and French, to the purchaser of the hazardous product\neither in hard copy or by electronic means.\nSDS must be updated within 90 days of the supplier becoming aware of new information that\nchanges how the hazardous product is classified or the way it will be handled or stored.\n\nHAZARDOUS PRODUCT INVENTORY\n• ETR will complete an inventory of all the hazardous products used or stored at each site.\n• This inventory must be reviewed and updated annually or as changes are required.\n• The most current review date will appear on the inventory list.\n• An inventory must be maintained for all the different groups/departments using or storing\nany type of chemicals.\n\nYEARLY REVIEW\n\nETR in conjunction with JHSC/WC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual basis or\nmore often if necessary.", "takeaways": ["3. A person who performs work or supplies services for no monetary compensation under a", "4. REPEALED: 2017, c. 22, Sched. 1, s. 71 (2).", "5. Such other persons as may be prescribed who perform work or supply services to an employer", "Educate workers on the potential health and safety hazards associated with", "Prevent chemical-related accidents, incidents, injuries, and illnesses."]}, {"id": "hazard-assessment", "title": "Hazard Assessment Program", "start": 74, "end": 77, "category": "Hazard Control", "text": "No. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-021\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 27-May-2025\nHAZARD ASSESSMENT PROGRAM Revision 2025.1\n\nPURPOSE\nThe purpose of the hazard assessment is to identify and evaluate the conditions that could lead\nto workers getting hurt or becoming ill. Hazard assessments and controls are the core of every\norganization’s occupational health and safety system.\n\nAll workers of ETR shall report any hazards that they are aware of, to their supervisor or\nmanager immediately. ETR Managers/Supervisors shall investigate all reported hazards as soon\nas they are made aware of them. ETR shall eliminate and/or control hazards to minimize risks.\n\nHAZARD ASSESSMENT PROCEDURE\nHazard Recognition\nBefore hazards can be eliminated or controlled, they must first be recognized as a hazard.\nHazard - is any source of potential damage, harm or adverse health effects on something or\nsomeone.\nEvery workplace consists of five major contributing factors:\n1. People (employees, visitors, suppliers, sub-contractors, etc.).\n2. Environment they work in.\n3. Materials they work with; and\n4. Equipment and tools they use.\n5. Process of how and when things are done\nHazard Assessment\nHazard Assessments shall be conducted on all Job tasks, projects/worksites in the form of a\nthorough look at the workplace to identify what actual and potential hazards exist.\nThe Hazard Assessment Form shall be used to document the tasks, hazards, current and\npotential controls.\nRecommendations should be made to eliminate or control each of the hazardous conditions\nidentified. The recommendations should include specific actions required to correct the\nproblem.\nHazards are identified during JHSC monthly inspections and they are inputted into the Health\nand Safety Action item tracker, the tracker shall be Managed by the Terminal Manager to ensure\nitems are assigned and taken care of efficiently.\nETR must be able to demonstrate that all existing and potential hazards have been identified.\n\nEmployer\n• Assess the workplace and identify existing and potential hazards before work begins at the\nworkplace or prior to the construction of a new workplace.\n• Prepare a report of the results of the hazard assessment and methods used to control or\neliminate the hazards identified.\n• Ensure that the date on which the hazard assessment is prepared or revised is recorded on it;\nand\n• Ensure that the hazard assessment is repeated at reasonable intervals, when a new work\nprocess is introduced, when a work process or operation changes, or before the construction\nof significant additions or alterations to the workplace.\nSupervisor/Manager\n\nUpon receiving a hazard reporting form, or upon becoming aware of a workplace hazard,\nsupervisors and members of management must:\n\n• Complete the second part of the hazard report form within 24 hours of receiving it.\n• Make recommendations regarding how to control the hazard and establish a corrective action\nplan for carrying out those recommendations.\n• Assign a member of management, or a supervisor, or both, to implement the corrective action\nplan and to ensure that the hazard is eliminated or control.\n• Confirm completion and execution of the corrective action plan.\n• File and maintain a record of the hazard report.\n• If applicable, submit the complete hazard report form and corrective action plan to\nmanagement and to the JHSC, as the case may be (if applicable); and\n• Advise the worker who reported the hazard of the outcome of the report and corrective\naction plan.\n• Conduct hazard assessments on daily job tasks/activities to ensure adequate controls of the\nrecognized hazards.\n• Shall email reported hazards (verbal or written) to all site management and supervisors and\ninput identified hazards into the Action tracker for full transparency.\n• Collaborate with JHSC/WC.\n\nWorker Participation\n• ETR will involve workers in hazard assessment, elimination, and control activities. Workers\nare often very knowledgeable about the tasks or processes being assessed and can be\ndirectly affected by the hazard elimination and control activities.\n• All workers are required to report hazards to their manager, supervisor as soon as they are\naware of a hazard. This initial report could be done verbally and the supervisor/manager\nshall document.\n• If the verbal reported hazard has not been actioned, then the employee shall fill out the\nHazard Reporting Form and submit to Director of Operations and the Corporate Health and\nSafety Specialist.\n\nHazard Elimination and Control\nHazard controls are the method of preventing or controlling worker exposure to health and\nsafety hazards. ETR shall assess and develop a method of control to reduce and/or eliminate\nthese risks.\nWhenever possible, hazards should be eliminated or controlled at the source using engineering\nsolutions. If this is not possible, controls should be placed between the source and the workers.\nThe closer a control is to the source of the hazard the better. If this is not possible, hazards must\nbe controlled at the level of the worker through administrative controls and personal protection\nequipment (PPE). There is a specific standard process in the management of hazards that must\nbe followed to assure that the best system of control is realized. This is referred to as\nthe “Hierarchy of Controls.”\n\nTYPES OF CONTROLS\nENGINEERED CONTROLS\nEngineering controls provide the highest degree of worker protection because they eliminate or\ncontrol the hazard at its source.\nEngineering controls include the following:\n● Elimination – getting rid of a hazardous job, tool, process, machine, or substance.\n● Substitution – if elimination is not practical, try substituting or replacing one substance or\nprocess with another.\n● Redesign – hazards can sometimes be “engineered out” through redesign of the worksite,\nstations.\n● Isolation – hazards can sometimes be isolated through containment or enclosure.\n● Automation – some processes can be automated or mechanized.\n\nAdministrative Controls\nIf engineering controls cannot eliminate or control a hazard, administrative controls can be used\nto reduce the risk of the hazard. Administrative controls are process and procedure related.\nChanging the way, the job is managed reduces the risk of injury. Safe work procedures (work\ninstructions) are administrative tools that provide safe work guidance. Administrative controls\nare less effective than engineering controls since they do not eliminate the hazards.\n\nPersonal Protective Equipment (PPE)\nAs a last resort, workers may need to use PPE to reduce the potentially harmful effects of\nexposure to a known hazard. PPE must be used properly and consistently to be effective.\nETR may use a combination of engineering controls, administrative controls and/or Personal\nprotective equipment that results in a greater level of worker safety than if each was used\nindividually.\n\nEVALUATION OF CONTROLS\nETR, along with the JHSC/WC shall evaluate the newly established controls to determine their\neffectiveness.\n\nYEARLY REVIEW\n\nETR in conjunction with JHSC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual basis or more\noften if necessary.", "takeaways": ["1. People (employees, visitors, suppliers, sub-contractors, etc.).", "2. Environment they work in.", "3. Materials they work with; and", "4. Equipment and tools they use.", "5. Process of how and when things are done"]}, {"id": "boots", "title": "Safety Boot Policy", "start": 78, "end": 78, "category": "PPE", "text": "Types of Hazards\n\nTypes of Hazards\n\nBiological\nbacteria, viruses, insects, plants, birds, animals, and humans, etc.\nHazards\n\ndepends on the physical, chemical, and toxic properties of the\nChemical Hazards\nchemical.\n\nErgonomic repetitive movements, improper set up of workstation,\nHazards pushing/pulling, shift work, tools, etc.\n\nradiation, indoor air quality, temperature extremes, pressure\nPhysical Hazards\nextremes, noise, etc.\n\nPsychosocial\nstress, conflict between job demands, violence, harassment, etc.\nHazards\n\nslipping/tripping hazards, inappropriate machine guarding,\nSafety Hazards\nequipment malfunctions or breakdowns.\n\nTHE ESSEX TERMINAL RAILWAY COMPANY\nSAFETY BOOT POLICY\n\nThe Essex Terminal Railway is committed to the safety of our employees, contractors, and visitors.\nEach worker is exposed daily to foot and ankle injury hazards. Due to the nature of work and\nresponsibilities, management has evaluated hazards that require the use of PPE such as protective", "takeaways": ["bacteria, viruses, insects, plants, birds, animals, and humans, etc.", "depends on the physical, chemical, and toxic properties of the", "Ergonomic repetitive movements, improper set up of workstation,", "Hazards pushing/pulling, shift work, tools, etc."]}, {"id": "vests", "title": "Safety Vest Policy", "start": 79, "end": 82, "category": "PPE", "text": "footwear. Management has designated the types of PPE that will protect against these hazards to\nminimize risk and injury to the employee.\n\nAs of January 01, 2019 employees will be required to have as part of their PPE, 8 inch CSA approved,\n“Green Triangle” toe capped boots with puncture-resistant soles. All employees must wear their\nfootwear properly for maximum protection. Boots must be tied securely to the top, if equipped with\nlaces, to help protect against ankle sprains caused by rolling over on the ankle.\n\nThe employee will be reimbursed for the cost of their footwear as per their collective agreement. The\nemployee will be responsible for the reasonable care and maintenance of the footwear. All\nemployees will be responsible for wearing their protective footwear while performing any work\nrelated activities.\n\nTHE ESSEX TERMINAL RAILWAY COMPANY\nSAFETY VEST POLICY\n\nThe Essex Terminal Railway is committed to the safety of our employees, contractors, and visitors.\nEach worker is exposed daily to personal injury risk or hazards. Due to the nature of work and\nresponsibilities, management has evaluated hazards that require the use of PPE such as High-\nvisibility safety apparel. Anytime someone is on ETR Property they are required to wear High-\nVisibility safety apparel (e.g., Vest, Shirts, Bibs or Coveralls.)\n\nHigh-Visibility safety apparel (HVSA) is clothing that workers can wear to improve how well other\npeople \"see\" them. Most often, High-Visibility clothing is worn to alert drivers, locomotive\nengineers, equipment operators and coworkers of employee's presence, especially in low light and\ndark conditions. High-Visibility items allow you to be seen by the drivers of those vehicles (cars,\ntrucks or other machinery traveling under their own power - e.g., forklifts, backhoes, locomotives\netc.) sooner and more readily. This fact increases your safety at work. The human eye responds\nbest to large, contrasting, bright or moving objects. Worker visibility is enhanced by high colour\ncontrast between clothing and the work environment against which it is seen.\n\nDuring working hours, all employees of the Essex Terminal Railway must wear High-Visibility safety\napparel as per Essex Terminal Railway Personal Protective Equipment Requirements. All High-\nVisibility safety clothing must meet CSA Standard Z96-15 for High-Visibility Safety Apparel.\n\nDuring working hours, all employees who are required to cross Lincoln Road, MUST wear High-\nVisibility safety apparel. Employees crossing Lincoln Road before or after working hours to reach\nthe parking areas are encouraged to wear High-Visibility safety apparel.\n\nIn addition to the above, all employees entering the Engine House, in the vicinity of Track\nMaintenance or the Repair Track, MUST wear High-Visibility safety apparel AT ALL TIMES.\n\nTo comply with the ETR and CSA Standard, the HVSA should meet the following criteria;\n\nCOLOUR:\nBackground material must be fluorescent orange, bright orange or fluorescent yellow, bright\nyellow.\n\nSTRIPES/BANDS:\na. A waist-level horizontal stripe/band that goes completely around the HVSA.\nb. Two vertical stripes on the front passing over the shoulders and down to the waist.\nc. A symmetric \"X\" on the back extending from the shoulders to the waist.\nd. Stripes/bands encircling both arms and both legs are added on coats and coveralls.\n\nCARE/MAINTENANCE:\n• Keep your high-visibility apparel clean and well-maintained. Contaminated or dirty\nreflective materials provide lower visibility.\n• Replace garments that show signs of wear and tear, soiling, or contamination as it will no\nlonger be able to provide acceptable levels of visibility.\nPurchasers of HVSA should get proof that the materials used and the design of the garment meet\nthe requirements of the CSA Z96-15 Standard.\n\nIt is also the responsibility and duty of all supervisors to ensure that any and all visitor(s) who enter\non to the Essex Terminal Railway property, wear proper protective equipment for the area they are\nin.\n\nOur goal is to provide all of our employees with a High-Visible presence in an ongoing effort toward\nsafety.", "takeaways": ["Keep your high-visibility apparel clean and well-maintained. Contaminated or dirty", "Replace garments that show signs of wear and tear, soiling, or contamination as it will no"]}, {"id": "ppe", "title": "Personal Protective Equipment Policy and Program", "start": 83, "end": 85, "category": "PPE", "text": "PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT REQUIREMENTS\nOPERATING DEPARTMENT\nAll Operating employees will wear personal protective equipment that will include but not limited\nto if employees require additional protection:\n\nYARDMASTERS (Not required when in office) AND TRAINMEN;\n1. Safety Glasses\n2. 8” Safety Boots\n3. High-Visibility Safety Apparel (Vest, T-Shirts, Sweatshirt or Coat)\n4. Work Gloves\n5. Long Pants\n6. Hard Hats when required by customer specific PPE requirements\n\nENGINEMEN;\n1. Safety Glasses*\n2. 8” Safety Boots\n3. High-Visibility Safety Apparel (Vest, T-Shirts, Sweatshirt or Coat)**\n4. Work Gloves when required\n5. Long Pants\n\n*Safety glasses are not required to be worn inside the cab of the Locomotive when windows are\nclosed.\n**High-Visibility Safety Apparel is not required to be worn inside the cab of the Locomotive.\n\nHOSTLERS;\n1. Safety Glasses*\n2. 8” Safety Boots\n3. High-Visibility Safety Apparel (Vest, T-Shirts, Sweatshirt or Coat)**\n4. Work Gloves when required\n5. Long Pants\n\nCutting goggles will be worn when using oxy-acetylene torch for cutting, heating & brazing.\n\nWelding helmet when welding.\n\nFull face piece respirator mask at minimum when cutting, grinding, welding in enclosed areas\n\nFull face piece respirators are to be worn when sanding engines, using the power washer with\nsoap, or spraying chemicals; eg. Electrical equipment.\n\nEar protection when around wheel cutting, wheel grinding or anywhere loud noise may occur.\n\nHard Hats must be worn when using overhead chain falls; eg. Motor rebuilds, when cranes are\nbeing used; eg. Wheel changes, and when there is any danger of anything falling from\noverhead. When working under engines bump hats may be worn in lieu of hard hats.\n\nEmployees will put Blue Flag Procedure into effect while working on railcars on any track, as per\nC.R.O.R. 26.\n\nOnly employees who have been trained and certified in the Operation of the Lift Truck & Scissor Lift\nand Fall Protection are authorized to use this equipment.\n\n*Safety glasses are not required to be worn inside the cab of the Locomotive when windows are\nclosed or worn inside any company vehicles when windows are closed.\n**High-Visibility Safety Apparel is not required to be worn inside the cab of the Locomotive or inside\nany company vehicle.\n\nMECHANICAL DEPARTMENT\nAll Mechanical employees will wear personal protective equipment that will include but not limited\nto if employees require additional protection:\n\nCAR INSPECTION;\n1. Safety Glasses*\n2. 8” Safety Boots\n3. High-Visibility Safety Apparel (Vest, T-Shirts, Sweatshirt or Coat)**\n4. Work Gloves when required\n5. Long Pants\n6. Hard Hats**\n\n*Safety glasses are not required to be worn inside any company vehicles when windows are closed.\n**High-Visibility Safety Apparel and Hard Hats are not required to be worn inside any company\nvehicles.\n\nEmployees while inspecting will put the Blue Flag Procedure into effect.\n\nCAR REPAIR;\n1. Safety Glasses\n2. 8” Safety Boots\n3. High-Visibility Safety Apparel* (Coveralls, Vest, T-Shirts, Sweatshirt or Coat)\n4. Work Gloves\n5. Long Pants\n6. Hard Hats\n\n*Exception to High-Visibility Safety Apparel will be made while wearing leather welding jacket,\nwhen necessary. At the time of wearing PPE that is not High-Visibility, orange pylons will be put in\nthe work area for protection.)\n\nEmployees will wear cutting goggles when using oxy-acetylene torch for cutting, heating, brazing.\n\nEmployees will wear welding helmet while welding.\n\nEmployees when cutting and welding under railcars, leather pants and leather jacket which are\nprovided will be worn.\n\nEmployees at minimum when cutting, welding, grinding inside railcars or in the engine house or other\nenclosed area will wear appropriate respirator masks.\n\nEmployees will put Blue Flag Procedure into effect while working on railcars on any track.\n\nOnly employees who have been trained and certified in the Operation of the Lift Truck – Scissor Lift\nand Fall Protection, are authorized to use this equipment.\n\nMAINTENANCE OF WAY DEPARTMENT\nAll Maintenance of Way employees will wear personal protective equipment that will include but\nnot limited to if employees require additional protection:\n\nTRACK DEPARTMENT;\n1. Safety Glasses*\n2. 8” Safety Boots\n3. High-Visibility Safety Apparel (Coveralls, Vest, T-Shirts, Sweatshirt or Coat)**\n4. Work Gloves\n5. Long Pants\n6. Hard Hats**\n7. Hearing protection\n\n*Safety glasses are not required to be worn inside any company vehicles when windows are closed.\n**High-Visibility Safety Apparel and Hard Hats are not required to be worn inside any company\nvehicles.\n\nFREIGHT OFFICE\nAll Freight Office employees will wear personal protective equipment that will include but not\nlimited to if employees require additional protection:\n\n*Safety glasses are not required to be worn inside any company vehicles when windows are closed.\n**High-Visibility Safety Apparel are not required to be worn inside any company vehicles.\n\nAnyone NOT wearing the above Personal Protective Equipment while working on ETR, CNR, CPR or\nanyone of our Customers property will be subject to discipline.", "takeaways": ["1. Safety Glasses", "2. 8” Safety Boots", "3. High-Visibility Safety Apparel (Vest, T-Shirts, Sweatshirt or Coat)", "4. Work Gloves", "5. Long Pants"]}, {"id": "msd", "title": "Musculoskeletal Disorder Policy and Program", "start": 86, "end": 88, "category": "Ergonomics", "text": "No. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-025\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 5-June-2025\nMUSCULOSKELETAL DISORDER POLICY AND Revision 2025.1\nPROGRAM\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\n\nETR is committed to preventing musculoskeletal disorder injuries and hazards causing the disorder\nin correlation to work conditions and job demands. Ergonomics is the relationship between people\nand their working equipment with a view to improving safety, ease of action and efficiency.\n\nSCOPE\n\nThis policy and program is applicable to all managers/supervisors and workers who may be\nexposed to the possibility of MSI/MSD.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\n\nThe employer shall:\n\n• develop, implement, monitor and review job tasks.\n• ensure that workers are adequately trained in ergonomics and material lifting/handling.\n• where practicable, provide appropriate equipment, tools to reduce possibility of MSI.\n• Review incidents related to MSDs in order to properly assess and control these hazards.\n\nManagers/Supervisors shall:\n\n• ensure proper equipment use and safe manual handling techniques by workers.\n• monitor controls measures effectiveness and advise all workers of known or foreseeable\nhazards.\n• take immediate steps to investigate and control MSI hazards that have been reported.\n\nWorkers shall:\n\n• use proper lifting techniques and the equipment provided for heavy or awkward loads.\n• report to the employer and/or supervisor any suspected risk factors associated with work.\n• Assist with MSD risk factors identification, workplace evaluations and\ndeveloping/implementing controls.\n• participate in training regarding MSD awareness and prevention.\n\nJHSC/WC will provide consultation regarding best practices, implementing control measures\nand conducting a regular review of activities performed that may cause or aggravate MSD’s.\n\nTRAINING AND EDUCATION\nThe company will train workers in all aspects of MSD Prevention and awareness including proper\nergonomics along with lifting and handling techniques. Additional training includes identification\nof the early signs and symptoms of musculoskeletal injury and their potential health effects, and\npreventive measures including, where applicable, the use of altered work procedures,\nmechanical aids and personal protective equipment. The company will keep records of training.\n\nMUSCULOSKELETAL DISORDERS (MSDS) PROGRAM\n\nSIGNS and SYMPTOMS OF MSD INJURIES\n\nThere are two types of MSI/MSD:\n• Overexertion – Occur suddenly when body is pushed too hard and attempts to lift, lower,\npush, pull or carry something that is too heavy.\n• Overuse – Develops over time when a worker repeatedly does the same task or\nmovement without sufficient recovery.\n\nThe following are a list of symptoms (not all inclusive):\n• Pain,\n• numbness,\n• tightness, reduced flexibility,\n• tingling,\n• swelling and redness\n\nMSD symptoms may go away overnight and could be a sign of fatigue, but if they are continuous,\nthis may indicate a more serious problem. Workers experiencing such symptoms should report\nsymptoms to their supervisor and health and safety. There may be individual differences in\nsusceptibility and symptoms among workers performing similar tasks.\n\nHAZARD RECOGNITION\n\nThe potential risk factors causing MSD are identified as:\n\n• force required,\n• posture, repetition,\n• contact stress,\n• vibration,\n• cold stress,\n• and mechanical compression.\n\nHAZARD ASSESSMENT\nThe purpose of the hazard assessment is to identify and evaluate the conditions where the\npotential exists of MSD or injury in the handling and lifting of products/items and how to\nmitigate. The company will conduct risk assessments in conjunction with the JHSC/WC.\n\nCONTROL MEASURES\nEngineering\n\n• Mechanical lifting aids such as hoists, pallet jacks, carts, instead of manual handing.\n• Invest in anti-fatigue mats for those workers that stand a lot, or work on hard services\nsuch as concrete.\n• Modify equipment or furniture to eliminate or reduce awkward postures.\n• Change to the workstations or equipment that alters the physical composition of the area.\nAdministrative\n\n• Rotating tasks between workers.\n• Use safe work procedures to minimize risk factors.\n• Heavy items are located at knee and waist height and light items above shoulder height.\n• Change task design.\n• Give workers time to rest or recover when lifting or handling loads.\n\nPersonal Protective Equipment (PPE)\n\n• Ensure gloves fit properly. Padded, friction-enhanced or vibration limiting\ngloves.\n• Workers that are required to kneel - knee pads or a kneeling pad can be\nused.\n• Warm clothing if workers have to work in cold conditions.\n\nPOLICY REVIEW\nThis policy/program will be reviewed at least annually and updated as necessary by the\ncompany, in consultation with the JHSC/WC.\n\nDEFINITIONS\n\nMusculoskeletal Disorders (MSD)- An injury or disorder of the muscles, tendons, ligaments,\njoints, nerves, blood vessels, or related soft tissue that may be caused or aggravated by work.\n\nMusculoskeletal Injury (MSI)- is an injury or disorder that affects the muscles, tendons,\nligaments, joints, or other soft tissues. MSIs can be caused by work, repetitive motions, or\nawkward positions\n\nErgonomics - The scientific study of the relationship between people and their working\nequipment with a view to improving safety, ease of action and efficiency", "takeaways": ["develop, implement, monitor and review job tasks.", "ensure that workers are adequately trained in ergonomics and material lifting/handling.", "where practicable, provide appropriate equipment, tools to reduce possibility of MSI.", "Review incidents related to MSDs in order to properly assess and control these hazards.", "ensure proper equipment use and safe manual handling techniques by workers."]}, {"id": "lifting", "title": "Lifting Devices Policy and Procedure", "start": 89, "end": 91, "category": "Equipment", "text": "No. ETR-MT-H&S-028\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 8-May-2025\nLIFTING DEVICES POLICY and PROCEDURE Revision 2025.1\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to ensuring the health and safety of everyone in the workplace by protecting\nand enhancing a positive encompassing culture through the safe operation of all types of lifting\ndevices (overhead cranes, hoists, jib cranes, stackers) at any of the company’s workplaces. It\nrecognizes the importance of workers and employers working together to identify and resolve\nhealth and safety issues in the workplace.\n\nSCOPE\nThis Policy applies to all employees, contractors, who regularly or occasionally may operate a\nlifting device while performing tasks at any site for the company. Lifting devices, are a vital part\nof operations at ETR.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBIITIES\nEmployers\n• Provide competent supervision based on training, knowledge, and experience.\n• Ensure that only those workers trained and deemed competent will be allowed to operate\nlifting devices. Copies of training must be retained.\n• Ensure pre-use inspections are conducted and documented.\n• Ensure adequate time for operators to perform pre-use inspections.\n• Ensure documented periodic inspections of overhead cranes as per classes E and F (quarterly)\nare conducted by certified technicians.\n• Instruct workers on the policy and procedure to ensure complete understanding.\n• Ensure that workplace hazards, causes of incidents, near misses are documented and\ninvestigated.\n• Work in conjunction with the JHSC on the management of the program.\n• The company shall follow requirements under the OHSA, Regulation 851, CSA B167-16 and all\nother applicable codes and standards.\nManagers/Supervisors\n• Ensure operators receive documented training conducted by a competent trainer.\n• Provide operators with access to manufacturer’s operating manuals for safe use and proper\nmaintenance.\n• Provide and collect a copy of the filled-out pre-use inspections prior to the lifting device\nbeing used for the first time on shift.\n• Shall review training matrix to ensure operators certification is current.\n\nWorkers/Operators\n• Only operate if the proper training, certification, and instruction is completed.\n• Shall operate lifting devices in a safe, responsible manner that is in accordance with training\nreceived.\n• Shall complete a visual and functional inspection prior to using the lifting device per shift.\n• Shall complete an inspection of all required rigging devices.\n• Shall document the inspections on a checklist prior to daily use of the specific lifting device.\n\nHAZARD IDENTIFICATION\nIt is the requirement of the operator to actively recognize and report hazards to their supervisor\nas soon as they are recognized. It is the duty of the supervisor to actively record and address\nthese hazards.\nTRAINING\nThe company shall ensure that workers that operate lifting devices are competent and\ncertified. Operators receive recertification at intervals not exceeding three years.\nThe company shall conduct a refresher course to ensure competency in situations such as the\nfollowing:\n• Operator has been observed operating the lifting device in an unsafe manner.\n• Operator has been involved in an accident.\n• Operator is assigned a different type of lifting device.\n• Environmental conditions in the workplace change.\n\nFACILITY HAZARDS\nThe company shall:\n\n• Conduct risk assessments in all areas that lifting devices are operating (warehouses, yards,\nmaintenance shops)\n• Ensure that the operators travel path is kept clear and free of hazards.\n• Ensure consistent grading of the yard to reduce negative outcome of operations while using\nlifting device, reduce possible equipment and material damage.\n• Adequate lighting must be provided wherever lifting devices are operating. If this is not\npractical, portable lighting shall be provided that illuminates the working area.\n• Pedestrians must wear highly visible clothing at all times.\n\nSAFE OPERATING GUIDELINES\n• Lifting device operators must be certified to use the type(s) of Lifting devices being used.\n• No part of a load may pass over any worker.\n• No load may exceed the maximum rated load capacity of any part of the lifting device.\n• When a load is in suspended position, the controls must be attended by an operator.\n• Loads should be carried as close to the ground or floor as possible.\n\n•Loads that may tip or fall and endanger a worker must be secured.\n•When a Lifting device is required to load or unload a vehicle (truck), the vehicle must be\nimmobilized and secured against accidental movement.\n• A Lifting device left unattended must be left in the lowered position and immobilized and\nsecured against accidental movement.\n• All load weight information either through manifest or appropriate calculations specified\nshould be made readily available to the Lifting device operator prior to lift.\n• Passengers are never allowed in the Lifting device.\n• As far as reasonably practical, the company shall restrict pedestrian access to areas where\nLifting devices are operating.\n• If a Lifting device operator believes that the load being moved is unsafe, the operator shall\ncontact their supervisor.\n• Lifting device operator shall utilize the horn whenever practical.\n• Operator shall ensure good housekeeping practices in areas of lifting device operations.\nMAINTENANCE\nThe company shall schedule and implement a preventative maintenance program to ensure all\nLifting devices are maintained as per guidelines in owner’s manuals.\nEnsure any modifications and additions that affect capacity or safe operation of the Lifting\ndevice are approved by certified engineer.\nPOLICY REVIEW\nThe company in conjunction with JHSC/WC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual\nbasis or more often if necessary.", "takeaways": ["Provide competent supervision based on training, knowledge, and experience.", "Ensure that only those workers trained and deemed competent will be allowed to operate", "Ensure pre-use inspections are conducted and documented.", "Ensure adequate time for operators to perform pre-use inspections.", "Ensure documented periodic inspections of overhead cranes as per classes E and F (quarterly)"]}, {"id": "mewp", "title": "Mobile Elevated Work Platform Policy and Procedure", "start": 92, "end": 94, "category": "Equipment", "text": "No. ETR-MT-H&S-030\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 8-May-2025\nMOBILE ELEVATED WORK PLATFORM POLICY and Revision 2025.1\nPROCEDURE\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to ensuring the health and safety of everyone in the workplace by protecting\nand enhancing a positive encompassing culture through the safe movement of Mobile Elevated\nWork Platforms throughout all the company’s workplaces. This policy is to define the\nrequirements for employees regarding use of mobile elevating work platforms and other\nequipment that elevates an employee to a height, including – selection, inspections,\nmaintenance, operation and fall protection systems. It recognizes the importance of workers\nand employers working together to identify and resolve health and safety issues in the\nworkplace.\n\nSCOPE\nThis Policy applies to all employees, contractors, who regularly or occasionally may operate an\nMEWP while performing tasks at any site for the company. MEWP’s, are a vital part of\noperations at ETR.\nTypes of mobile elevating work platforms this policy applies to are:\n• Self-Propelled Elevating Work Platform (scissor lift)\n• Forklift Aerial Platforms\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\nEmployer\nETR shall ensure compliance with this policy and in conjunction with the fall protection policy\nand procedure.\n• Ensure policies, safe work procedures are implemented and followed.\n• Ensure all equipment, owned, or rented, meets legislative requirements, and is deemed safe\nfor operation.\nSupervisors\n• Ensure employees receive the training and certification specific to the mobile elevating work\nplatforms and equipment they will be using. Ensure employees are not operating MEWP\nwithout proper authorization.\n• Ensure all documentation and training records are maintained.\n• Ensure preventive maintenance is completed and records are maintained for mobile elevated\nwork platforms.\n• Ensure a pre job planning assessment is conducted.\n\n• Ensure hazard assessments are conducted of the job, equipment, and worker safety to ensure\nall hazards are identified and mitigated.\n• Ensure communication of this policy and the fall protection policy and procedure and specific\nwork procedures to all applicable employees.\n• Develop and communicate rescue plans and other emergency procedures for working on\nmobile elevating work platforms.\nEmployees\n• Must follow this policy and instructions.\n• Do not operate equipment without valid certification and training.\n• Must inspect all equipment, tools, and personal protective equipment before use and\ndocument inspections.\n• Conduct a hazard assessment prior to starting work.\n\nHAZARD ASSESSMENTS\nA hazard assessment shall be completed to identify and assess the need for the use of the\nmobile elevated work platform and hazards specific to the tasks.\nA hazard assessment should include but not limited to:\n• Work environment.\n• Weather conditions.\n• Ground, floor, surface, slope, debris.\n• Inadequate surface and support to withstand all load forces imposed by the elevated work\nplatform.\n• Fall prevention.\n• Overhead obstructions, overhead power lines.\n• Other vehicles, pedestrians.\n• Emergency preparedness and response.\n• When dealing with traffic and pedestrians that cannot be eliminated from the work area, set\nup barriers around where the MEWP is operating.\nTRAINING REQUIREMENTS\nAll workers must be authorized to operate an elevating work platform by completing theoretical\nand practical certified training. If not included, they must complete fall protection training. The\noperator must be familiar with:\n\n• all operating instructions.\n• conduct pre-use inspections.\n• factors affecting stability.\n• the use of fall protection systems.\n• Must take into account the weight of all loads bearing on the equipment – limitations of the\nbasket (refer to the rated capacity on placard located on the equipment).\n• Knowledge of lifting restrictions.\n• Clearance requirements.\n\nINSPECTION AND MAINTENANCE RECORDS\nDetailed reports of inspection, maintenance, repairs, and modifications must be kept\npermanently for the duration of the service life of the MEWP and available on request by\nManagement, JHSC and MLITSD.\nA manufacturer’s manual is to be kept with the equipment or readily available.\nA periodic inspection of the MEWP is recommended to be performed by a qualified person after\n200 hours or more often if recommended by the manufacturer.\nAnnual inspection of the MEWP is recommended every 12 months from the prior annual\ninspection or 700 hours of use. This is to be done by a qualified person.\nStructural inspections are required on a MEWP after 10 years from the manufacture date or if\nany suspected or potential damage occurs due to an accident that would affect the structural\nintegrity. This inspection must be carried out under the direction of a professional engineer.\nOperators shall conduct pre use inspections according to the manufacturer’s specifications and\nmaintain these records in a logbook with the equipment.\nOperators must ensure that each set of controls be clearly identified to indicate their functions,\nhas an emergency stop device within easy reach of the operator (must be labelled STOP and\ncoloured red) and warning devices automatically activated when the MEWP is in motion and can\nbe heard.\nA maintenance and inspection record tag shall be provided and attached to the mobile elevating\nwork platform near the operator's station and must include:\n\n• the date of the last maintenance and inspection.\n• the signature and name of the person who performed the maintenance and inspection.\n\nFALL PROTECTION\nOperators of mobile elevating work platforms are required to have fall protection training and\nalways use personal fall protection. Only lifts equipped with proper anchor points are to be\nused. Fall protection SHALL be used at all times when the equipment is in motion.\n\nRESCUE PLAN\nA rescue plan for the MEWP is required and can involve a spotter watching the operator. The\nspotter must be trained in how to lower the MEWP in the event of an emergency. The controls\nmust include a clearly marked overriding lowering control that will enable a worker at the lower\ncontrols to stop and lower the platform in an emergency.\n\nYEARLY REVIEW\n\nETR in conjunction with JHSC/WC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual basis or\nmore often if necessary.", "takeaways": ["Self-Propelled Elevating Work Platform (scissor lift)", "Forklift Aerial Platforms", "Ensure policies, safe work procedures are implemented and followed.", "Ensure all equipment, owned, or rented, meets legislative requirements, and is deemed safe", "Ensure employees receive the training and certification specific to the mobile elevating work"]}, {"id": "forklift", "title": "Forklift Policy and Procedure", "start": 95, "end": 97, "category": "Equipment", "text": "No. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-027\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 6-May-2025\nFORK LIFT POLICY and PROCEDURE Revision 2025.1\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to ensuring the health and safety of everyone in the workplace by protecting\nand enhancing a positive encompassing culture through the safe movement of forklifts\nthroughout all the company’s workplaces. It recognizes the importance of workers and\nemployers working together to identify and resolve health and safety issues in the workplace.\n\nSCOPE\nThis Policy applies to all employees, contractors, who regularly or occasionally may operate a\nforklift while performing tasks at any site for the company. Forklifts, are a vital part of\noperations at ETR.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBIITIES\nEmployers\n• Provide competent supervision based on training, knowledge, and experience.\n• Ensure that only those workers trained and deemed competent will be allowed to operate\nany forklift. Copies of training must be retained.\n• Ensure pre-use inspections are conducted and documented.\n• Ensure adequate time for operators to perform pre-use inspections.\n• Ensure documented annual inspections as per manufacturer’s specifications are conducted\nby certified technicians.\n• Instruct workers on the policy and procedure to ensure complete understanding.\n• Ensure that workplace hazards, causes of incidents, near misses are documented and\ninvestigated.\n• Work in conjunction with the JHSC on the management of the program.\n• The company will ensure the selection of a forklift will meet the needs and requirements of\nits operations.\nManagers/Supervisors\n• Ensure operators receive documented training conducted by a competent trainer.\n• Provide operators with access to manufacturer’s operating manuals for safe use and proper\nmaintenance.\n• Provide and collect a copy of the filled-out pre-use inspections prior to forklift being used for\nthe first time on shift.\n• Shall review training matrix to ensure operators certification is current.\n\n• Arrange for forklifts to receive an annual inspection by a qualified mechanic.\nWorkers/Operators\n\n• Only operate if the proper training, certification, and instruction is completed.\n• Use forklifts in a safe, responsible manner that is in accordance with training received.\n• Complete a pre-operative checklist prior to daily use of forklifts.\nHAZARD IDENTIFICATION\nIt is the requirement of the operator to actively recognize and report hazards to their\nsupervisor. It is the duty of the supervisor to actively record and address these hazards.\nTRAINING\nThe company shall ensure that workers that operate forklifts are competent and\ncertified. Operators receive recertification at intervals not exceeding three years.\nThe company shall conduct a refresher course to ensure competency in situations such as the\nfollowing:\n\n• Operator has been observed operating the forklift in an unsafe manner.\n• Operator has been involved in an accident.\n• Operator is assigned a different type or class of forklift.\n• Environmental conditions in the workplace change.\nFACILITY HAZARDS\nThe company shall:\n\n• Ensure that overhead and side clearances, loading docks and doorways are adequate to\npermit safe operation of the forklift and to accommodate the load being moved.\n• Ensure that the forklift’s travel path is kept clear and free of hazards.\n• Ensure consistent grading of the yard to reduce negative impact on the operator, reduce\npossible equipment and material damage.\nAdequate lighting must be provided wherever forklifts are operating. If this is not practical, the\nforklift should be equipped with lighting that illuminates the working area.\nPedestrians and workers in the vicinity of forklift operations must be kept safe:\n• Pedestrians must wear highly visible clothing at all times.\n• Ensure that any storage racks being used are suitable for the type of forklift(s) being used;\nsuitable, strong, and sturdy enough for the loads being supported.\n• Outdoor yards have additional hazards that must be controlled, including safe walking paths,\nsmooth surfaces, and adequate lighting.\nSAFE OPERATING GUIDELINES\n● Forklift operators must be certified to use the type(s) of forklifts being used.\n● Forklift operator must use a seat belt at all times.\n● No part of a load may pass over any worker.\n● No load may exceed the maximum rated load capacity.\n● All loads must be handled in accordance with the height and weight restrictions on the\nforklifts load chart.\n\n● When a load is in the raised position, the controls must be attended by an operator.\n● Loads should be carried as close to the ground or floor safely.\n● Loads that may tip or fall and endanger a worker must be secured.\n● When a forklift is required to load or unload a vehicle (truck), the vehicle must be immobilized\nand secured against accidental movement.\n● Maintain sufficient air quality in areas where internal combustion engine forklifts are used, to\ncontrol carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide hazards.\n● A forklift left unattended must be immobilized and secured against accidental movement.\n● All load weight information either through manifest or appropriate calculations specified\nshould be made readily available to the forklift operator before the start of lifting operations.\n● Passengers are never allowed in the forklift.\n● As far as reasonably practical, the company shall restrict pedestrian access to areas where\nforklifts are operating.\n● If a forklift operator believes that the load being moved is unsafe, the operator shall contact\ntheir supervisor.\n● Forklift operator shall utilize the horn whenever practical and especially when reversing.\n● Ensure it is equipped with adequate and properly operating headlights and tail lights when\nused after dark or in dimly lit areas.\n● Operator shall maintain the forklift is reasonable condition as it relates to housekeeping. The\ncab, shall be kept clean, free of debris and garbage. Flashlights, tools, first aid kits, etc. shall\nbe securely stored.\nREFUELING\nRefueling should be done in an area with adequate ventilation to prevent the accumulation of\nflammable vapours. Open flames in the refueling area are prohibited.\nAn appropriate class and size fire extinguisher must be in close proximity to the refueling\noperation and the operator must be trained on its use.\nThe forklift must be turned off, properly parked and the operator out of the forklift during\nrefueling.\nMAINTENANCE\nThe company shall schedule and implement a preventative maintenance program to ensure all\nforklifts are maintained as per guidelines in owner’s manuals.\nEnsure any modifications and additions that affect capacity or safe operation of the forklift are\nperformed with the written approval of the manufacturer or a qualified professional engineer.\nPOLICY REVIEW\nThe company in conjunction with JHSC/WC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual\nbasis or more often if necessary.\n\nNo. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-031", "takeaways": ["Provide competent supervision based on training, knowledge, and experience.", "Ensure that only those workers trained and deemed competent will be allowed to operate", "Ensure pre-use inspections are conducted and documented.", "Ensure adequate time for operators to perform pre-use inspections.", "Ensure documented annual inspections as per manufacturer’s specifications are conducted"]}, {"id": "fall", "title": "Fall Protection Policy and Procedure", "start": 98, "end": 100, "category": "Working at Heights", "text": "HEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 13-May-2025\nFALL PROTECTION POLICY and PROCEDURE Revision 2025.1\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to ensuring the health and safety of everyone in the workplace by protecting\nand enhancing a positive encompassing culture through the safe use of fall protection\nequipment. It recognizes the importance of workers and employers working together to identify\nand resolve health and safety issues in the workplace.\n\nSCOPE\nThis Policy applies to all employees, contractors, and visitors who regularly or occasionally work\nat heights and are exposed to the hazard of falling. Everyone who carries out work at heights or\nis exposed to the risk of falling from a height of more than 3 meters (10 feet) must receive\nspecialized training. Working at heights includes work on sloped or flat roofs, in circumstances\nwhen adequate railings are not provided and may also include working on ladders or other\nelevated pieces of equipment or surfaces.\nFall protection must be used when a worker may be exposed to any of the following hazards:\n• Fall from a temporary or permanent work area, a vertical distance of three (3) meters or\nmore.\n• Fall from a vertical distance of less than three (3) meters where there is an unusual\npossibility of injury.\n• Falling into water or another liquid.\n• Fall at a temporary or permanent work area, into or onto a hazardous substance or object.\nGuardrails or other similar means of fall restraint must be used when practicable. If not\npracticable, a fall arrest system must be used.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\nEmployers\n• Develop a written fall protection policy and procedures relevant to the workplace.\n• Provide the necessary resources that are required to implement the Policy.\n• Ensure employees receive the necessary training for working at heights.\n• Identify areas where there is potential for workers to fall and get injured.\n• Provide workers with the necessary personal protective equipment (PPE) required to work\nsafely.\n• Create and develop a rescue plan in some situations and provide employees with the\nnecessary equipment and training to carry out the rescue plan.\nSupervisors/Managers\n• Be aware of and enforce the requirements outlined in this Policy.\n• Conduct hazard assessment for each and every working at heights job task to be performed\nand this assessment shall be communicated to all involved in the task.\n• Whenever possible, eliminate any work that may expose workers to fall hazards.\n\n• Ensure that employees are provided with any required fall protection equipment, are trained\nin the equipment, and competent in the safe use, care, and maintenance of the equipment.\n• Ensure that fall arrest and travel restraint systems are inspected by a competent person\nbefore and after each use and that defective equipment is taken out of service immediately.\n• Ensure, as according to manufacturer's guidelines, that an annual inspection and\nrecertification of all systems be conducted by a certified 3rd party.\nEmployees\n• Be aware of and adhere to the requirements outlined in this Policy.\n• Perform a hazard assessment before work begins to identify any hazards that could lead to\nfalls and injuries.\n• Actively participate in fall protection education and training.\n• Use PPE required for the task, ensure proper care and maintenance of the PPE.\n• Inspect personal fall protection systems before each use and document.\n• Notify the supervisor or employer about any broken, defective, or missing protective\nequipment. Be aware of your right to refuse unsafe work.\n• Complete working at heights training to be deemed a competent person\nContractors/sub-contractors/constructors\n• Be aware of and adhere to the requirements outlined in this Policy.\n• Perform hazard assessments and control any fall-related hazards that are identified.\n• Report all incidents or injuries.\n• Have a working at heights program as applicable per Construction Regulations that meets or\nexceeds all the conditions outlined in this Policy.\n• Ensure all employees have been trained in working at heights and have a valid and up-to-\ndate certificate.\n• Provide a copy of Training certificates to the Corporate Health and Safety Specialist.\nTRAINING\nAll employees of ETR who are required to use fall protection equipment will be trained in its use\nby a competent person. Employees must be retrained by a competent trainer at least every\nthree (3) years.\nETR may also require its workers to be retrained in the safe use of fall protection system under\ncircumstances that include but not limited to changes in the workplace which render previous\ntraining obsolete, changes in the types of fall protection systems, or inadequacies in an affected\nemployee’s knowledge or use of fall protection systems.\nIn addition to the training described, workers will be made aware of the fall hazards particular\nto the work sites they are working at, and the steps being taken by ETR to eliminate or control those\nhazards.\n\nINSPECTIONS\nThe inspection process is a critical step in preventing accidents that are caused from faulty or\nworn-out equipment.\n\nAll fall protection components must be inspected by the employee before and after each use.\nAnnual inspections must also be performed on all components by a competent professional.\nAll fall protection systems, equipment, and components must be:\n● maintained in good working condition.\n● Stored in identified location\nWhen safety-related concerns have been discovered through the inspections, or at any other\ntime, the manager must be notified, and the equipment taken out of service immediately.\n\nREMOVAL FROM SERVICE\nAny fall protection equipment that is found to be defective must immediately be removed from\nservice.\nIf the fall arrest equipment has been utilized to stop a fall, the entire fall arrest system must be\nremoved from service and not returned to service until it has been re-certified.\n\nRESCUE PLAN\nETR shall develop written rescue procedures before workers can use any fall-arrest system or\nwhen working at heights involving elevated work platforms. A rescue plan needs to be job and\nsite-specific. Each job site will have its own set of unique conditions that need to be addressed\nin a rescue plan. The plan and its procedures must be reviewed with all employees involved.\nPlans should cover the on-site equipment, personnel, and procedures for different types of\nrescues. The rescue of suspended workers must happen as quickly as possible.\nExternal Rescue services may be utilized in some situations.\nSite management must ensure that:\n\n• everyone on site is aware of the rescue plan.\n• equipment and other resources are available to conduct a rescue.\n• designated personnel are properly trained.\n• any third-party Emergency Response Team that will be conducting the rescue has been\nnotified of the time, location, and date of the job (if applicable).\n\nRECORD RETENTION\nEquipment inspection and training records for work involving the use of fall protection must be\nmaintained by ETR and kept for a period of three years after the use of such equipment.\n\nPOLICY REVIEW\nETR in conjunction with JHSC/WC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual basis or\nmore often if necessary.\n\nNo. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-036\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date 11-Aug-2025", "takeaways": ["Fall from a temporary or permanent work area, a vertical distance of three (3) meters or", "Fall from a vertical distance of less than three (3) meters where there is an unusual", "Falling into water or another liquid.", "Fall at a temporary or permanent work area, into or onto a hazardous substance or object.", "Develop a written fall protection policy and procedures relevant to the workplace."]}, {"id": "incident", "title": "Incident Investigation Policy and Procedure", "start": 101, "end": 104, "category": "Incident Management", "text": "INCIDENT INVESTIGATION POLICY AND Revision 2025.1\nPROCEDURE\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to the health, safety and well-being of employees, contractors, and visitors\nthrough conducting thorough investigations of near misses and incidents in order to identify\ndirect, indirect and root causes. ETR is committed to finding root causes of all near misses,\nincidents in order to implement corrective actions to eliminate recurrences.\n\nSCOPE\nThis Policy applies to all employees, contractors, and visitors who may be onsite for any purpose\nat any of our three facilities and/or any of our leased or rented locations. This policy will cover\npersonal injuries and equipment near misses and incidents.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\nETR is committed to ensuring that all near misses and incidents involving injury are thoroughly\ninvestigated in a timely manner and results are reported to all internal stakeholders and\nexternal agencies.\n\nEmployers\n• Ensure that Managers/Supervisors Investigate all near misses, incidents in a timely manner\n• Provide competent supervision based on training, knowledge, and experience.\n• Ensure that Managers/Supervisors are trained and deemed competent to investigate\nworkplace incidents.\n• Ensure adequate time for Managers/Supervisors, JHSC/WC members to complete a thorough\ninvestigation of all incidents.\n• Shall provide training on investigation techniques\n• Instruct workers on the policy and procedure to ensure complete understanding.\n• Ensure that workplace hazards, causes of incidents, near misses are documented,\ninvestigated and corrective actions implemented.\nManagers/Supervisors\n• Initiate Emergency plan procedures when applicable\n• Contact all relevant personnel\n• Investigate all near misses and incidents in a timely manner\n• Communicate this policy/procedure to all employees.\n• Conducting periodic inspections of work areas.\n\nWorkers\n• Responsible for reporting all near misses and incidents.\n• Secure and manage the scene when no Manager/supervisor is present\n• Shall actively cooperate and participate in investigations when requested.\n\nPURPOSE\nReasons to investigate a workplace incident:\n\n• To determine the causes of the incident and to prevent similar incidents in the future\n• Help to reduce costs of injuries/equipment damage\n• To provide accurate and complete reports to all external agencies as required by applicable\nlegislation.\nPROCEDURES\nSTEPS:\n\n1. Secure and Manage the Scene: Managers/Supervisors/Workers\n\nNear Miss/Minor Incident\n\n• Ensure Emergency Plan Procedures as per location have been initiated\n• Assess injuries, provide first aid\n• Secure the area if required,\nMajor Incident:\n\n• Ensure Emergency Plan Procedures as per location have been initiated\n• Assess injuries, provide first aid and ensure all external resources have been called\n• Secure the area, establish a perimeter (barrier tape, cones)\n• Assess existing hazards and initiate immediate control measures when required\n• The scene shall remain undisturbed except for the purpose of saving life or relieving human\nsuffering or preventing unnecessary damage to equipment or property.\n• Contact Corporate Health and Safety Specialist (Mon-Fri, 8:00-4:00)\n• Contact Corporate Human Recourses (Mon-Fri, 8:30-4:30)\n• Contact a worker member of the JHSC/WC\n• Director of Operations shall contact Corporate Health and Safety Specialist if incident occurs\noutside the Mon-Fri hours of 8:00-4:00\n\n2. Collecting Data and Gathering Evidence\n\n• Pictures, sketches, taking measurements, interviewing witnesses, camera footage\n• Inspection reports, policies, maintenance records, training records, H&S records\n• After documenting observations and questioning witnesses, provide each witness with a\nwitness statement form and have them individually in separate areas fill those out.\nRecord all observations made at the scene, such as:\n\no Environmental conditions\no Date and time of the accident\no Condition of the worker\no Machine, tool, or equipment involved\no Task employee was performing\no Take several pictures and make notes\no Document all discussions\n\nWitness Questions:\n\no What Happened?\no Who was involved?\no Where did it occur?\no When did it occur?\no What were the conditions like? (weather, lighting, noise)\no What did you hear?\no What did you see?\no Where were you before and at the time of the incident?\no What were you doing?\no Did you observe anything out of the ordinary?\n\n3. Analyzing Evidence and Identifying Causes\n\no Collect all evidence from other investigation team members.\no Collectively go over the evidence.\no Are you aware of any Safe work procedure for this task?\no Have you ever performed this task?\no Have the team members involved in the incident received training and instruction?\no Are you aware of any similar incidents in the past?\no Was this incident related to any known Risks in the workplace?\no What equipment or materials played a role in this incident?\no Discuss the 5 WHY method to determine a Root cause\no Re-enactments or demonstrations may be required to analyze evidence\n4. Completing the Accident/Incident Investigation Form\n\nThe Report Should include:\n\n1. Pictures, recordings, drawings\n2. Direct and indirect causes, including contributing factors\n3. Immediate and long-term corrective actions.\n4. Submit the form\n\nRemember your audience – This document will be used to support all parties involved\n(Employer, employee, etc.) It may be reviewed by all Management, WSIB, Lawyers and in any\ncourt proceedings. If you did not believe a witness’ statement, make a note regarding the\nreasons for your skepticism. The report needs to be detailed, legible and accurate.\n\nNo accident investigation has ever changed what has already happened and therefore we\nshould never assign blame but instead should identify gaps in the safety process.\n\nACTION PLAN\n• Long term corrective actions shall have assigned responsibility along with a completion date\n• Actionable items shall be discussed and reviewed with the JHSC/WC\n• Corporate Health and Safety Specialist shall follow up on corrective actions to ensure they\nare implemented as discussed and done as designed.\n• Employees involved in a major incident may be subjected to a drug/alcohol test depending\non the severity and observations of the employee by Management.\n\n• To book Drug test you can send an email to appointmentbookings@drivercheck.ca or call us\non 1.800.463.4310 option 1.\n• If Drug/alcohol testing is required, the employee shall remain isolated while waiting for the\ntest to be administered.\n• If a lab-based drug/alcohol test is required, the Director of Operations and Corporate Human\nResources Manager shall decide on the next steps on a case-by-case basis.\nTOOLKITS: Each yard should have at least one incident investigation kit.\n- Phone/camera\n- Tape measure\n- Flashlight\n- Clipboard, pen, graph paper for illustrations\n- LOTO devices and tags\n- Barrier tape\nDefinitions:\nNear Miss- an unwanted, unplanned event that did not cause an injury or property damage but may\nhave done so if conditions had been slightly different.\n\nMinor incidents- An unwanted, unplanned event that caused a minor first aid treatable injury onsite or\nproperty damage that does not delay or impede operations.\n\nMajor incidents- An unwanted, unplanned event causing injury requiring external medical care and/or\nproperty damage that has forced a stoppage in operations. Critical Injuries/Fatality fall under Major\nincidents.\n\nCritically injured- means an injury of a serious nature that,\n(a) places life in jeopardy,\n(b) produces unconsciousness,\n(c) results in substantial loss of blood,\n(d) involves the fracture of a leg or arm but not a finger or toe,\n(e) involves the amputation of a leg, arm, hand or foot but not a finger or toe,\n(f) consists of burns to a major portion of the body, or\n(g) causes the loss of sight in an eye;\n\n5 Whys method- is a root cause analysis technique that involves repeatedly asking \"why\" to drill down\nfrom a problem's symptoms to its underlying cause. By asking \"why\" multiple times (typically five, but\nsometimes more or less), the goal is to uncover the fundamental issue that needs to be addressed to\nprevent the problem from recurring\n\nViolence and Harassment Investigations- Refer to Provincial Violence and Harassment Program\nProcedure MT-MPL-HR-002, Federal Violence and Harassment Program Procedure ETR-HR-012\n\nWork Refusal Investigations- Refer to Provincial Work Refusal Policy and Procedure MT-MPL-H&S-022,\nFederal, refer to ETR employee handbook. THE ESSEX TERMINAL RAILWAY COMPANY WORK REFUSAL\nPOLICY.", "takeaways": ["Ensure that Managers/Supervisors Investigate all near misses, incidents in a timely manner", "Provide competent supervision based on training, knowledge, and experience.", "Ensure that Managers/Supervisors are trained and deemed competent to investigate", "Ensure adequate time for Managers/Supervisors, JHSC/WC members to complete a thorough", "Shall provide training on investigation techniques"]}, {"id": "confined", "title": "Confined Space Policy and Procedure", "start": 105, "end": 109, "category": "High-Risk Work", "text": "No. ETR-H&S-037\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective Date DRAFT\nCONFINED SPACE POLICY AND PROCEDURE Revision 2025.1\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to the health, safety and well-being of employees, contract employees that are\nrequired to work in confined spaces. ETR shall ensure the required training and necessary\nequipment is in compliance with all applicable local and federal regulations\n\nSCOPE\nThis Policy applies to all employees, contractors, who regularly or occasionally may be part of a\nteam required to work in a confined space. Identified confined spaces, grain hopper rail cars,\nservice pit in engine house.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\n\nEmployer shall:\n• Ensure all workers are trained and comply with this policy.\n• Ensure all required equipment for tasks to be completed safely are provided.\n• Ensure rescue procedures, equipment have been communicated and available.\n• Ensure a rescue team has been established, trained and available in the area of the\nconfined space during entry into the confined space.\n• Identify and create a log of confined spaces and hazardous confined spaces.\n• Appoint a qualified/competent person to determine whether a confined space is a\nhazardous confined space.\n• Ensure that a sign or marking at the entrance of the confined space clearly indicates the\ntype of confined space. (confined space or hazardous confined space)\n• Appoint a qualified person to conduct a hazard assessment and provide the signed and\ndated report to the employer. Copy of the report must be provided to the Workplace\ncommittee. This report shall be reviewed every 3 years or sooner if confined space\nstructures change or the task completed in the confined space.\n• Create safe work procedures for working in a confined space.\n\nSupervisors/Managers\n• Implement and train all employees on this policy.\n• Ensure suitable training in the risks associated with tasks must be given to all relevant\npersonnel.\n• Ensure that all required equipment, tools, and PPE are available to execute the work\nsafely.\n• Ensure trained rescue staff is onsite and available if required\n• Ensure proper training documentation is completed and retained\n• Investigate incidents arising in the application of this policy, implementing necessary\ncorrective actions following an incident or the identification of a risk or hazard.\n• Complete required documentation prior to assigning tasks to be completed in a confined\nspace.\n• Create safe work procedures for confined space work.\nWorkers\n• Comply with the requirements of this policy.\n• Report any incidents, near misses, risks or hazards\n• Participate in and complete all necessary training\n\n• Wear all provided PPE required for the tasks\n• Maintain and care for all PPE\n• Complete required documentation prior to entering confined space\n\nPROCEDURES\n1. A qualified person shall assess possible confined spaces to identify if they are a confined\nspace and what type.\n2. Hazard assessments shall be conducted for each identified confined space. If two or more\nare similar in construction and the same hazards exist, the assessment can be reported in\none document, but it shall clearly identify each space.\n3. Hazard assessments shall be made available to the WC and every employee that may enter\ninto the confined space or be involved in the tasks.\n4. Identify the need to ventilate or purge the confined space if applicable. Natural ventilation\nmay be suitable. (hopper gates and roof latches are fully opened; safety hazards have been\ncontrolled)\n5. Conduct a tailboard meeting to discuss the plan and tasks to be completed in the confined\nspace.\n6. Ensure 2-way communication and person check systems are in place and working\nproperly.\n7. Complete entry permit with the following information for a confined space:\na. Name of person entering the space\nb. Date and time of entry anticipated date and time of exit and the actual date and\ntime of exit.\n8. Fill out Entry Permit into a hazardous confined space:\n9. Name of person entering the space\n10. Date and time of entry anticipated date and time of exit and the actual date and time of\nexit.\n11. Atmospheric testing is conducted prior to entry and continuously while in the confined\nspace. Testing equipment must be calibrated and maintained in accordance with the\nmanufacturer’s instructions.\n12. Ensure attendant is stationed outside confined space and near the entrance\n13. Ensure the entrant has inspected and wearing a harness; Entrant is attached at all times\nwhile in the confined space (railcar)to above SRL through the open hatch.\n14. Enter the confined space and complete the task.\n15. Continuous monitoring of air contaminants if applicable.\n16. Record monitoring results on entry permit.\n17. Complete all tasks, sign off and close out the entry permit.\n\nEMERGENCY PROCEDURES\n\n1. If the entrant team member becomes unresponsive inside the confined space, notify\nManagement immediately to call 911. This is the responsibility of the on-site\nSupervisor/ Emergency Coordinator in consultation with the first aid / C.P.R. attendant.\n\n2. Call for additional team member support, assess the entrant's condition and, if possible,\nattempt to retrieve him by reaching in through the hopper gate opening.\n3. Once the team member is out of the confined space, immediately begin First Aid/CPR.\n4. Isolate the area to prevent unauthorized access and to eliminate other potential\nhazards.\n5. Ensure a team member is positioned at Lincoln rd. to direct emergency services to\nlocation.\n6. If the entrant team member becomes injured but conscious while in the confined space,\nthe attendant shall assess the severity of injuries and mental state by asking questions.\n7. Depending on injuries, the entrant may be able to self-rescue from the confined space,\nbut if not, a first aider shall either enter the confined space to provide first aid or\ncarefully retrieve the entrant through the hopper gate opening. Once the team member\nis out of the confined space, immediately begin First Aid/CPR.\n8. If team member requires medical attention, a member of the Management team shall\nbe notified immediately to call 911.\n9. Under no circumstances should equipment, materials, etc. be moved or operated until\nthe injured person is stabilized or unless it is necessary to prevent further injury.\n10. If the Accident/Incident involves machinery or equipment, Entanglement/Entrapment;\non site staff with appropriate expertise shall be made available without delay.\n\nWe also have a boom attachment for the forklift that could be utilized if a rescue is\nneeded through the top of the rail car\n\nHuman Resources will notify the injured person's next of kin only after:\n\nSTATUS OF THE SITUATION IS KNOWN and, the injured person's condition is known and\nstable, or the injured person is in the care and custody of emergency services and in\ntransit to a medical facility.\n\nDefinitions:\n“Atmospheric hazards” means,\n(a) the accumulation of flammable, combustible or explosive agents,\n(b) an oxygen content in the atmosphere that is less than 19.5 per cent or more than 23\nper cent by volume, or\n(c) the accumulation of atmospheric contaminants, including gases, vapours, fumes,\ndusts or mists, that could,\n(i) result in acute health effects that pose an immediate threat to life, or\n(ii) interfere with a person’s ability to escape unaided from a confined space;\n\nConfined space means a space that\n\n(a) is enclosed or partially enclosed;\n\n(b) is not designed or intended for continuous human occupancy; and\n\n(c) has a limited or restricted means of entry or exit or an internal configuration that\ncould complicate provision of first aid, evacuation, rescue or other emergency response.\n\nHazardous confined space means a confined space that, when entered, occupied or exited by\npersons, presents hazards likely to cause injury, illness or other adverse health effects to persons\nentering, exiting or occupying it because of\n\nc) its design, construction, location or atmosphere;\nc) the materials or substances in it; or\nc) any other conditions relating to it\nc)\n\nCombustibles are materials that can burn, meaning they can ignite and sustain a flame when\nexposed to a heat source.\n\nSupporting Policies and Procedures\nHazard Assessment Program (ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-021)\nHazard Assessment Form (ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-052)\nVessel to Land Emergency Transfer Policy and Procedure (ETR-MT-H&S-029)\nIncident Investigation Policy and Procedure (ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-036)\nFirst Aid Policy and Procedure (ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-024)\nETR Emergency Plan Procedure (ETR-H&S-013)\nPOLICY REVIEW\nThis policy is to be reviewed annually and updated as necessary in conjunction with the WC to ensure\ncompliance.", "takeaways": ["Ensure all workers are trained and comply with this policy.", "Ensure all required equipment for tasks to be completed safely are provided.", "Ensure rescue procedures, equipment have been communicated and available.", "Ensure a rescue team has been established, trained and available in the area of the", "Identify and create a log of confined spaces and hazardous confined spaces."]}, {"id": "driving", "title": "Safe Driving Policy and Procedure", "start": 110, "end": 111, "category": "Vehicles", "text": "No. ETR-MT-MPL-H&S-034\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective 28-July-2025\nDate\nSAFE DRIVING POLICY and PROCEDURE Revision 2025.1\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to complying with all standards based on the policies, procedures, processes,\nand manufacturer’s specifications for the safe operation of company vehicles/equipment. The\ngoal is to eliminate incidents and increase safety by promoting a safe driving culture on\nworksites.\n\nSCOPE\n\nThis Policy applies to all employees, contractors, who regularly or occasionally may operate any\nETR vehicle or equipment while performing tasks at any site for the company.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\n Employers\n● Ensure that all company vehicles are maintained as according to regulatory requirements\nand manufacturer’s specifications.\n● Ensure that all operators of company vehicles/equipment are properly licensed/certified,\ncomply with applicable safety and traffic legislation, comply with company rules and policies,\nand demonstrate safe driving habits.\n● Ensure that near misses and incidents are reported, documented, and investigated.\n● Ensure that all operators conduct documented pre-use inspections.\n● If applicable, ensure that an onsite traffic control plan is in place to avoid interactions with\nother vehicles, mobile equipment, and pedestrians.\n Supervisors/Managers\n● Ensure that all company vehicles/equipment are maintained properly and in good safe\ncondition.\n● Ensure that documented pre-use inspections are conducted.\n● Ensure the operator is certified to operate.\n● Ensure all company vehicle operators are trained on the traffic control plan for the site, if\napplicable.\n● Ensure all near misses or incidents are reported, documented, and reviewed.\n● Investigate all incidents, determine cause, and recommend corrective actions to prevent\nreoccurrence.\n Operators\n● Must be trained, qualified, licensed and authorized to operate the vehicle.\n● All vehicles must be inspected before use. A walk around shall be completed to check for\npossible hazards. Report vehicle defects to a supervisor before use and document.\n● Ensure that all required registration, permits, and insurance certificates are stored in the\ncab.\n● Security of loads/emergency equipment must also be checked.\n● Pedestrians have the right of way.\n● Notify supervisor immediately if their driver’s license has been suspended, cancelled, or\nlimited in any way.\n● Must be trained and aware of the Traffic Control Plan for the worksite, if applicable.\n● Avoid/eliminate distracting behaviors while driving (e.g., texting, use of handheld cell\nphones/devices, eating, grooming, reading, playing with multi-media devices, etc.).\n● Do not drive if physical or mental condition is adversely impacted or if weather or site\nconditions are hazardous.\nGENERAL REQUIREMENTS\n● All signs governing the movement and parking of vehicles on any worksite must be\nobserved.", "takeaways": ["SAFE DRIVING POLICY and PROCEDURE Revision 2025.1", "ETR is committed to complying with all standards based on the policies, procedures, processes,", "and manufacturer’s specifications for the safe operation of company vehicles/equipment. The", "goal is to eliminate incidents and increase safety by promoting a safe driving culture on"]}, {"id": "hearing", "title": "Hearing Conservation Program", "start": 112, "end": 115, "category": "Occupational Health", "text": "● Operators are to obey posted speed limits at all times. If unsure of posted speed limit,\nalways take lower possible speed.\n● Follow safe fueling practices (e.g., no smoking, check for leaks, don’t overfill, do not leave\nnozzle unattended, no cell phone or PDA use).\n● Ensure all applicable safety and emergency features/equipment are fully operational and\navailable (e.g., back up alarm, seat belts, fire extinguisher, first aid kit, warning\nflares/triangles, flashlight, cold weather emergency supplies, etc.).\n● Keep cab and floor of vehicle or motorized equipment free of materials, tools or other\nobjects that could interfere with the operation of the controls, create hazards, or create a\nprojectile hazard in the event of an accident. When objects must be carried in the cab,\nensure objects are secured.\n● Do Not back up when other reasonable and practicable options exist to avoid having to\nperform this potentially hazardous activity (e.g., where possible, plan dump or pickup\nlocations to allow drive in/out option). Take measures to ensure back up, where required, is\nas safe as possible (e.g., use signalperson, do circle check, engage back up alarm, park such\nthat the first move when leaving is forward).\n● Ensure nothing obstructs the driver’s vision or impairs driver’s use of controls (e.g., Signs,\nStickers, labels, logbooks, etc.).\n● Encourage safe driving behaviour (e.g., regular breaks, management of work schedules to\nensure adequate rest breaks as required by law, defensive driving, etc.).\n● Assess surrounding area prior to start-up and movement to ensure movement is not a\nhazard to the operator, workers, or the public (i.e., circle check).\n● Do not leave the controls of vehicles or motorized equipment unattended unless it is\nsecured against unintentional movement.\n● Do not leave vehicles/equipment idling when not in use.\nYEARLY REVIEW\n\nETR in conjunction with JHSC/WC shall review this policy and procedure on an annual basis\nor more often if necessary.\n\nNo. ETR-H&S-034\n\nHEALTH AND SAFETY Effective 9-Feb-2026\nDate\nHEARING CONSERVATION PROGRAM Revision 2026.1\n\nPOLICY STATEMENT\nETR is committed to the health, safety and well-being of employees, contract employees that\nmay be exposed to excessive levels of noise while performing tasks for the company. ETR shall\nensure the required training, hearing protection, signage of noise hazard areas, annual hearing\n\ntest along with record keeping are all in compliance with all applicable local and federal\nregulations\n\nSCOPE\nThis Policy applies to all employees required to wear hearing protection to perform their daily\njob tasks. The Engineers, Brakeman and Conductors, MOW (Maintenance of Way) team\nmembers are all required to wear hearing protection at all times while performing any job tasks.\nCar department employees shall wear hearing protection when performing specific tasks\npreviously identified.\n\nROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\nEmployer shall:\n\n• Ensure all workers are trained and comply with this program.\n• Ensure all required equipment for tasks to be completed safely are provided.\n• Schedule an initial audiometric test for all current identified employees and new hires.\n• Schedule and allocate time for each identified employee to have an audiometric test\ncompleted after the first year and then we will follow the TC regulations.\n• Provide hearing protection, training of proper fit and care of hearing protection.\n• Create and install signage in all areas of concern such as on the locomotives, engine house\nand MOW vehicles.\n• Conduct noise-exposure testing when equipment, tasks change.\n• Cover all costs associated with this hearing conservation program.\n\nSupervisors/Managers shall:\n\n• Implement and train all employees on this program.\n• Ensure hearing protection is provided and available in all areas that require protection.\n• Encourage and enforce the use of hearing protection.\n• Demonstrate proper fit techniques to ensure protection.\n\nWorkers shall:\n\n• Comply with the requirements of this program.\n• Participate in and complete all necessary training.\n• Participate in annual hearing tests.\n• Report any other noise level concerns to their supervisor that has not been previously\nidentified.\n• Wear all provided PPE required for the tasks (hearing protection)\n• Maintain and care for all PPE\n\nPROCEDURES/REQUIREMENTS\n\n1. ETR Corporate Health and Safety Specialist conducted an assessment of possible excessive\nNoise levels in the workplace using a Niosh app on the phone in collaboration with\nmembers from the Workplace Committee.\na. The assessment was conducted in the cab of an engine (locomotive) in neutral and\nthrottle position mid-way, the levels exceeded the 87dBA\nb. ETR Corporate Health and Safety along with the workplace committee determined\nthat further assessments of noise levels needed to be conducted, a third party was\ncontracted to conduct this testing.\n2. IES Consulting conducted testing on Dec 2/2025 and Dec 3/2025, results are in the report\nprovided Dec 9/2025.\na. Report is available for review on the Health and Safety board as well discussed during\nthe next workplace committee meeting.\nb. Report results shall be communicated to all affected employees.\n3. Engineers, Brakeman, Conductors and the MOW department are all required to wear the\nprovided Honeywell Laser Lite earplugs with a Noise Reduction Rating of 32dBA.\n4. All identified employees shall be scheduled for an audiometric test as an initial assessment\nand on an annual basis.\n5. Record Keeping\ni. Education and training to employees\nii. Results of noise exposure measurements (10 years)\niii. Annual hearing test results\niv. Completed Hearing Conservation Program Checklist\n\nEDUCATION AND TRAINING\n\n• Noise is any unwanted sound that doesn’t happen in a natural environment. Noise can\ninclude sounds coming from machinery, highway traffic, and industrial, commercial and\nresidential sources.\n• Noise is caused by pressure changes in the air created by vibrations, which are\ntransferred to the ear by sound waves. The sound waves are then converted to\nelectrical signals by delicate hair cells called cilia, found in the inner ear, or\ncochlea. These signals are transmitted to the brain and interpreted as sound.\n• Exposure to loud noise breaks down the cilia and large groups of the cells often\nget torn away. When the cilia become damaged, they do not grow back and this\ncan cause permanent hearing loss.\n• You can prevent noise-induced hearing loss by eliminating or reducing hazardous\nnoise exposure in your workplace.\n\nWhy we use hearing protection\n\nNoise induced hearing loss (NIHL) is one of the most common work-related illnesses in Canada.\nHazardous workplaces that can cause NIHL are not always obvious. Sometimes infrequent but\nloud impact noises that occur sporadically can-do damage to hearing.\n\nOther adverse health effects of noise exposure include temporary threshold shift (TTS)\nand tinnitus. TTS is when noise exposure results in a temporary hearing loss that recovers after\nrest. A worker might have to turn up the car radio volume at the end of the work day, but will\n\nturn it back down the next morning. Repeated TTS can lead to a permanent threshold\nshift (PTS), or NIHL. Tinnitus is ringing or buzzing in the ears.\nUnfortunately, there is no official cure for NIHL. The best treatment is often hearing aids. There is\nno drug or medication that works for NIHL.\n\nHow does noise affect my hearing?\n\nA person with NIHL may struggle to hear speech sounds such as “sh”, “s”, “th” and “f”. It is most\nnoticeable at the start and end of a word; “shell”, “sell” and “fell” may be difficult to distinguish.\nThis makes speech sound more mumbled and less crisp or clear than it should.\n\nWhen should hearing protection be used?\n\nHearing protection shall be used where ever the hazards of excessive noise exposure has been\nidentified and communicated to the teams.\n\nWho is responsible to take care of the hearing protection?\n\nThe employee is responsible for the fit, care and maintenance of their PPE.\n\nPOLICY REVIEW\nThis policy is to be reviewed annually and updated as necessary in conjunction with the\nWorkplace Committee to ensure compliance.\nThe legislative requirements\n\nUnder the Regulations, your employer must maintain your noise exposure level at a level not\nexceeding 87 dBA, either by using engineering devices to reduce the noise or by shortening the\nduration of exposure. If, in spite of these efforts, your noise exposure level could exceed 87 dBA,\nyour employer must submit a report to Human Resources Development Canada - Labour\nProgram, with a copy to the work place health and safety committee or representative, and\nprovide you with adequate hearing protectors.", "takeaways": ["Ensure all workers are trained and comply with this program.", "Ensure all required equipment for tasks to be completed safely are provided.", "Schedule an initial audiometric test for all current identified employees and new hires.", "Schedule and allocate time for each identified employee to have an audiometric test", "Provide hearing protection, training of proper fit and care of hearing protection."]}, {"id": "life-savers", "title": "ETR Life Savers", "start": 116, "end": 116, "category": "Critical Rules", "text": "1. Secure equipment before action\nis taken.\n2. Protect employees against\nmoving equipment.\n3. Discuss safety at the beginning of\na job or when a project changes.\n4. Communicate before action is\ntaken.\n5. Mentor less experienced\nemployees to perform service\nsafely.", "takeaways": ["1. Secure equipment before action", "2. Protect employees against", "3. Discuss safety at the beginning of", "4. Communicate before action is", "5. Mentor less experienced"]}];
